# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: immunology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:immunology/complement-system] Despite being part of the innate immune system, the complement system can be recruited and brought into action by antibodies generated by the adaptive immune system.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The complement system consists of a number of small, inactive, liver synthesized protein precursors circulating in the blood.
[src:immunology/complement-system] When stimulated by one of several triggers, proteases in the system cleave specific proteins to release cytokines and initiate an amplifying cascade of further cleavages.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The end result of this *complement activation* or *complement fixation* cascade is stimulation of phagocytes to clear foreign and damaged material, inflammation to attract additional phagocytes, and activation of the cell-killing membrane attack complex.
[src:immunology/complement-system] About 50 proteins and protein fragments make up the complement system, including plasma proteins, and cell membrane receptors.
[src:immunology/complement-system] They account for about 10% of the globulin fraction of blood serum.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Three biochemical pathways activate the complement system: the classical complement pathway, the alternative complement pathway, and the lectin pathway.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The alternative pathway accounts for the majority of terminal pathway activation and so therapeutic efforts in disease have revolved around its inhibition.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In 1888, George Nuttall found that sheep blood serum had mild killing activity against the bacterium that causes anthrax.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The killing activity disappeared when he heated the blood.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In 1891, Hans Ernst August Buchner, noting the same property of blood in his experiments, named the killing property "alexin", which means "to ward off" in Greek.
[src:immunology/complement-system] By 1894, several laboratories had demonstrated that serum from guinea pigs that had recovered from cholera killed the cholera bacterium *in vitro*.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Heating the serum destroyed its killing activity.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Nevertheless, the heat-inactivated serum, when injected into guinea pigs exposed to the cholera bacteria, maintained its ability to protect the animals from illness.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Jules Bordet, a young Belgian scientist in Paris at the Pasteur Institute, concluded that this principle has two components, one that maintained a "sensitizing" effect after being heated and one (alexin) whose toxic effect was lost after being heated.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The heat-stable component was responsible for immunity against specific microorganisms, whereas the heat-sensitive component was responsible for the non-specific antimicrobial activity conferred by all normal sera.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Ehrlich introduced the term "complement" as part of his larger theory of the immune system.
[src:immunology/complement-system] According to this theory, the immune system consists of cells that have specific receptors on their surfaces to recognize antigens.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Upon immunization with an antigen, more of these receptors are formed, and they are then shed from the cells to circulate in the blood.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Those receptors, which we now call "antibodies," were called by Ehrlich "amboceptors" to emphasise their bifunctional binding capacity: They recognise and bind to a specific antigen, but they also recognise and bind to the heat-labile antimicrobial component of fresh serum.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Ehrlich, therefore, named this heat-labile component "complement," because it is something in the blood that "complements" the cells of the immune system.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Ehrlich believed that each antigen-specific amboceptor has its own specific complement, whereas Bordet believed that there is only one type of complement.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In the early 20th century, this controversy was resolved when it became understood that complement can act in combination with specific antibodies, or on its own in a non-specific way.
[src:immunology/complement-system] **Phagocytosis** – by opsonizing antigens.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3b has most important opsonizing activity.
[src:immunology/complement-system] **Inflammation** – by attracting macrophages and neutrophils.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Most of the proteins and glycoproteins that constitute the complement system are synthesized by hepatocytes.
[src:immunology/complement-system] But significant amounts are also produced by tissue macrophages, blood monocytes, and epithelial cells of the genitourinary system and gastrointestinal tract.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The three pathways of activation all generate homologous variants of the protease C3-convertase.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The classical complement pathway typically requires antigen-antibody complexes for activation (specific immune response), whereas the alternative pathway can be activated by spontaneous complement component 3 (C3) hydrolysis, foreign material, pathogens, or damaged cells.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The mannose-binding lectin pathway can be activated by C3 hydrolysis or antigens without the presence of antibodies (non-specific immune response).
[src:immunology/complement-system] In all three pathways, C3-convertase cleaves and activates component C3, creating C3a and C3b, and causes a cascade of further cleavage and activation events.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3b binds to the surface of pathogens, leading to greater internalization by phagocytic cells by opsonization.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In the alternative pathway, C3b binds to Factor B.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Factor D releases Factor Ba from Factor B bound to C3b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The complex of C3b(2)Bb is a protease which cleaves C5 into C5b and C5a.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C5 convertase is also formed by the classical pathway when C3b binds C4b and C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C5a is an important chemotactic protein, helping recruit inflammatory cells.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3a is the precursor of an important cytokine (adipokine) named ASP (although this is not universally accepted ) and is usually rapidly cleaved by carboxypeptidase B.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Both C3a and C5a have anaphylatoxin activity, directly triggering degranulation of mast cells as well as increasing vascular permeability and smooth muscle contraction.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C5b initiates the membrane attack pathway, which results in the membrane attack complex (MAC), consisting of C5b, C6, C7, C8, and polymeric C9.
[src:immunology/complement-system] MAC is the cytolytic endproduct of the complement cascade; it forms a transmembrane channel, which causes osmotic lysis of the target cell.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Kupffer cells and other macrophage cell types help clear complement-coated pathogens.
[src:immunology/complement-system] As part of the innate immune system, elements of the complement cascade can be found in species earlier than vertebrates; most recently in the protostome horseshoe crab species, putting the origins of the system back further than was previously thought.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The classical pathway is triggered by activation of the C1-complex.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The **C1-complex** is composed of 1 molecule of C1q, 2 molecules of C1r and 2 molecules of C1s, or *C1qr2s2*.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This occurs when C1q binds to IgM or IgG complexed with antigens.
[src:immunology/complement-system] A single pentameric IgM can initiate the pathway, while several, ideally six, IgGs are needed.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This also occurs when C1q binds directly to the surface of the pathogen.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Such binding leads to conformational changes in the C1q molecule, which leads to the activation of two C1r molecules.
[src:immunology/complement-system] They then cleave C1s (another serine protease).
[src:immunology/complement-system] The C1r2s2 component now splits C4 and then C2, producing C4a, C4b, C2a, and C2b (historically, the larger fragment of C2 was called C2a but is now referred to as C2b).
[src:immunology/complement-system] C4b and C2b bind to form the classical pathway C3-convertase (C4b2b complex), which promotes cleavage of C3 into C3a and C3b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3b later joins with C4b2b to make C5 convertase (C4b2b3b complex).
[src:immunology/complement-system] The alternative pathway is continuously activated at a low level, analogous to a car engine at idle, as a result of spontaneous C3 hydrolysis due to the breakdown of the internal thioester bond (C3 is mildly unstable in aqueous environment).
[src:immunology/complement-system] The alternative pathway does not rely on pathogen-binding antibodies like the other pathways.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3b that is generated from C3 by a C3 convertase enzyme complex in the fluid phase is rapidly inactivated by factor H and factor I, as is the C3b-like C3 that is the product of spontaneous cleavage of the internal thioester.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In contrast, when the internal thioester of C3 reacts with a hydroxyl or amino group of a molecule on the surface of a cell or pathogen, the C3b that is now covalently bound to the surface is protected from factor H-mediated inactivation.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The surface-bound C3b may now bind factor B to form C3bB.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This complex in the presence of factor D will be cleaved into Ba and Bb.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Bb will remain associated with C3b to form C3bBb, which is the alternative pathway C3 convertase.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The C3bBb complex is stabilized by binding oligomers of factor P (properdin).
[src:immunology/complement-system] The stabilized C3 convertase, C3bBbP, then acts enzymatically to cleave much more C3, some of which becomes covalently attached to the same surface as C3b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This newly bound C3b recruits more B, D and P activity and greatly amplifies the complement activation.
[src:immunology/complement-system] When complement is activated on a cell surface, the activation is limited by endogenous complement regulatory proteins, which include CD35, CD46, CD55 and CD59, depending on the cell.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Pathogens, in general, don't have complement regulatory proteins (there are many exceptions, which reflect adaptation of microbial pathogens to vertebrate immune defenses).
[src:immunology/complement-system] Thus, the alternative complement pathway is able to distinguish self from non-self on the basis of the surface expression of complement regulatory proteins.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Host cells don't accumulate cell surface C3b (and the proteolytic fragment of C3b called iC3b) because this is prevented by the complement regulatory proteins, while foreign cells, pathogens and abnormal surfaces may be heavily decorated with C3b and iC3b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Accordingly, the alternative complement pathway is one element of innate immunity.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Once the alternative C3 convertase enzyme is formed on a pathogen or cell surface, it may bind covalently another C3b, to form C3bBbC3bP, the C5 convertase.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This enzyme then cleaves C5 to C5a, a potent anaphylatoxin, and C5b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The C5b then recruits and assembles C6, C7, C8 and multiple C9 molecules to assemble the membrane attack complex.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This creates a hole or pore in the membrane that can kill or damage the pathogen or cell.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The lectin pathway is homologous to the classical pathway, but with the opsonin, mannose-binding lectin (MBL), and ficolins, instead of C1q.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This pathway is activated by binding of MBL to mannose residues on the pathogen surface, which activates the MBL-associated serine proteases, MASP-1, and MASP-2 (very similar to C1r and C1s, respectively), which can then split C4 into C4a and C4b and C2 into C2a and C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C4b and C2b then bind together to form the classical C3-convertase, as in the classical pathway.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Ficolins are homologous to MBL and function via MASP in a similar way.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Several single-nucleotide polymorphisms have been described in M-ficolin in humans, with effect on ligand-binding ability and serum levels.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Historically, the larger fragment of C2 was named C2a, but it is now referred to as C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In invertebrates without an adaptive immune system, ficolins are expanded and their binding specificities diversified to compensate for the lack of pathogen-specific recognition molecules.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Immunology textbooks have used different naming assignments for the smaller and larger fragments of C2 as C2a and C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The preferred assignment appears to be that the smaller fragment be designated as C2a: as early as 1994, a well known textbook recommended that the larger fragment of C2 should be designated C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] However, this was amplified in their 1999 4th edition, to say that: "It is also useful to be aware that the larger active fragment of C2 was originally designated C2a, and is still called that in some texts and research papers.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Here, for consistency, we shall call all large fragments of complement **b**, so the larger fragment of C2 will be designated C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This nomenclature is used in another literature: The assignment is mixed in the latter literature, though.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Some sources designate the larger and smaller fragments as C2a and C2b respectively while other sources apply the converse.
[src:immunology/complement-system] However, due to the widely established convention, C2b here is the larger fragment, which, in the classical pathway, forms C4b2b (classically C4b2a).
[src:immunology/complement-system] It may be noteworthy that, in a series of editions of Janeway's book, 1st to 7th, in the latest edition they withdraw the stance to indicate the larger fragment of C2 as C2b.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Fixation of the MBL protein on viral surfaces has also been shown to enhance neutralization of viral pathogens.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In the classical pathway, C1 binds with its C1q subunits to Fc fragments (made of CH2 region) of IgG or IgM, which has formed a complex with antigens.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C4b and C3b are also able to bind to antigen-associated IgG or IgM, to its Fc portion.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Such immunoglobulin-mediated binding of the complement may be interpreted as that the complement uses the ability of the immunoglobulin to detect and bind to non-self antigens as its guiding stick.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The complement itself can bind non-self pathogens after detecting their pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs), however, utilizing specificity of the antibody, complements can detect non-self targets much more specifically.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Some components have a variety of binding sites.
[src:immunology/complement-system] In the classical pathway, C4 binds to Ig-associated C1q and C1r2s2 enzyme cleaves C4 to C4b and 4a.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C4b binds to C1q, antigen-associated Ig (specifically to its Fc portion), and even to the microbe surface.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3b binds to antigen-associated Ig and to the microbe surface.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Ability of C3b to bind to antigen-associated Ig would work effectively against antigen-antibody complexes to make them soluble.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The complement system has the potential to be extremely damaging to host tissues, meaning its activation must be tightly regulated.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The complement system is regulated by complement control proteins, which are present at blood plasma and host cell membrane.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Some complement control proteins are present on the membranes of self-cells preventing them from being targeted by complement.
[src:immunology/complement-system] One example is CD59, also known as protectin, which inhibits C9 polymerization during the formation of the membrane attack complex.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The classical pathway is inhibited by C1-inhibitor, which binds to C1 to prevent its activation.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Another example is a plasma protein called Factor H (FH), which has a key role in down-regulating the alternative pathway.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Factor H, along with another protein called Factor I, inactivates C3b, the active form of C3.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This process prevents the formation of C3 convertase and halts the progression of the complement cascade.
[src:immunology/complement-system] C3-convertase also can be inhibited by decay accelerating factor (DAF), which is bound to erythrocyte plasma membranes via a GPI anchor.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Complement regulation is suggested to play a role in pregnancy.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Improper alternative complement pathway activation may mediate recurrent immune-mediated fetal loss.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The complement system is also becoming increasingly implicated in diseases of the central nervous system such as Alzheimer's disease and other neurodegenerative conditions such as spinal cord injuries.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Deficiencies of the terminal pathway predispose to both autoimmune disease and infections (particularly Neisseria meningitidis, due to the role that the membrane attack complex ("MAC") plays in attacking Gram-negative bacteria).
[src:immunology/complement-system] Infections with *N. meningitidis* and *N. gonorrhoeae* are the only conditions known to be associated with deficiencies in the MAC components of complement.
[src:immunology/complement-system] 40–50% of those with MAC deficiencies experience recurrent infections with *N. meningitidis*.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Mutations in the genes of complement regulators, especially factor H, have been associated with atypical hemolytic uremic syndrome, and C3 glomerulopathy.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Both of these disorders are currently thought to be due to complement overactivation either on the surface of host cells or in plasma, with the molecular location of genetic variation in complement proteins providing clues into the underlying disease processes.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Moreover, several single nucleotide polymorphisms and mutations in the complement factor H gene (the most common of which results in the protein change p.Y402H) have been associated with the common eye disease age-related macular degeneration.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Polymorphisms of complement component 3, complement factor B, and complement factor I, as well as deletion of complement factor H-related 3 and complement factor H-related 1, also affect a person's risk of developing age-related macular degeneration.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Mutations in the C1 inhibitor gene can cause hereditary angioedema, a genetic condition resulting from reduced regulation of bradykinin by C1-INH.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria is caused by complement breakdown of RBCs due to an inability to make GPI.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Thus the RBCs are not protected by GPI anchored proteins such as DAF.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Diagnostic tools to measure complement activity include the total complement activity test.
[src:immunology/complement-system] The presence or absence of complement fixation upon a challenge can indicate whether particular antigens or antibodies are present in the blood.
[src:immunology/complement-system] This is the principle of the complement fixation test.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Excessive complement activity contributes to severe Covid-19 symptoms and disease.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Although complement is intended to protect the body systems, under stress there can be more damage than protection.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Research has suggested that the complement system is manipulated during HIV/AIDS, in a way that further damages the body.
[src:immunology/complement-system] Research from over the last decade has shown that complement proteins of the classical complement pathway have an important role in synaptic pruning in the brain during early development.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are usually too large to cross cell membranes and enter cells.
[src:immunology/cytokine] They typically function by interacting with specific cytokine receptors on the surface of target cells.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines include chemokines, interferons, interleukins, lymphokines, and tumour necrosis factors, but generally not hormones or growth factors (despite some overlap in the terminology).
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are especially important in the immune system, including in immune responses and inflammation.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines modulate the balance between humoral and cell-based immune responses, and they regulate the maturation, growth, and responsiveness of particular cell populations.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Some cytokines enhance or inhibit the action of other cytokines in complex ways.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are generally released in lower concentrations than hormones.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Immune cytokines released by one cell can send signals to the same cell (autocrine signaling), nearby cells (paracrine signaling), and other cells throughout the body (endocrine signaling).
[src:immunology/cytokine] The word comes from the ancient Greek language: *cyto*, from Greek κύτος, *kytos*, 'cavity, cell' + *kines*, from Greek κίνησις, *kinēsis*, 'movement'.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines have been classed as lymphokines, interleukins, and chemokines, based on their presumed cell of secretion, function, or target of action.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Because cytokines are characterised by considerable redundancy and pleiotropism, such distinctions, allowing for exceptions, are obsolete.
[src:immunology/cytokine] A key focus of interest has been that cytokines in one of these two sub-sets tend to inhibit the effects of those in the other.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Dysregulation of this tendency is under intensive study for its possible role in the pathogenesis of autoimmune disorders.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Several inflammatory cytokines are induced by oxidative stress.
[src:immunology/cytokine] The fact that cytokines themselves trigger the release of other cytokines and lead to increased oxidative stress makes them important in chronic inflammation, as well as other immunoresponses, such as fever and acute phase proteins of the liver (IL-1,6,12, IFN-a).
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines also play a role in anti-inflammatory pathways and are a possible therapeutic treatment for pathological pain from inflammation or peripheral nerve injury.
[src:immunology/cytokine] There are both pro-inflammatory and anti-inflammatory cytokines that regulate this pathway.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Classic hormones circulate in aqueous solution in nanomolar (10-9 M) concentrations that usually vary by less than one order of magnitude.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In contrast, some cytokines (such as IL-6) circulate in picomolar (10-12 M) concentrations that can increase up to 1,000 times during trauma or infection.
[src:immunology/cytokine] The widespread distribution of cellular sources for cytokines may be a feature that differentiates them from hormones.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Virtually all nucleated cells, but especially endo/epithelial cells and resident macrophages (many near the interface with the external environment) are potent producers of IL-1, IL-6, and TNF.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In contrast, classic hormones, such as insulin, are secreted from discrete glands such as the pancreas.
[src:immunology/cytokine] The current terminology refers to cytokines as immunomodulating agents.
[src:immunology/cytokine] A contributing factor to the difficulty of distinguishing cytokines from hormones is that some immunomodulating effects of cytokines are systemic (*i.e.*, affecting the whole organism) rather than local.
[src:immunology/cytokine] For instance, to accurately utilize hormone terminology, cytokines may be autocrine or paracrine in nature, and chemotaxis, chemokinesis and endocrine as a pyrogen.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Essentially, cytokines are not limited to their immunomodulatory status as molecules.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In this regard, and also because the redundancy and pleomorphism of cytokines are, in fact, a consequence of their homologous receptors, many authorities think that a classification of cytokine receptors would be more clinically and experimentally useful.
[src:immunology/cytokine] A classification of cytokine receptors based on their three-dimensional structure has, therefore, been attempted.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Such a classification, though seemingly cumbersome, provides several unique perspectives for attractive pharmacotherapeutic targets.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Each cytokine has a matching cell-surface receptor.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Subsequent cascades of intracellular signaling then alter cell functions.
[src:immunology/cytokine] This may include the upregulation and/or downregulation of several genes and their transcription factors, resulting in the production of other cytokines, an increase in the number of surface receptors for other molecules, or the suppression of their own effect by feedback inhibition.
[src:immunology/cytokine] The effect of a particular cytokine on a given cell depends on the cytokine, its extracellular abundance, the presence and abundance of the complementary receptor on the cell surface, and downstream signals activated by receptor binding; these last two factors can vary by cell type.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are characterized by considerable redundancy, in that many cytokines appear to share similar functions.
[src:immunology/cytokine] It seems to be a paradox that cytokines binding to antibodies have a stronger immune effect than the cytokine alone.
[src:immunology/cytokine] This may lead to lower therapeutic doses.
[src:immunology/cytokine] It has been shown that inflammatory cytokines cause an IL-10-dependent inhibition of T-cell expansion and function by up-regulating PD-1 levels on monocytes, which leads to IL-10 production by monocytes after binding of PD-1 by PD-L.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Adverse reactions to cytokines are characterized by local inflammation and/or ulceration at the injection sites.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Occasionally such reactions are seen with more widespread papular eruptions.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are crucial for fighting off infections and in other immune responses.
[src:immunology/cytokine] However, they can become dysregulated and pathological in inflammation, trauma, sepsis, and hemorrhagic stroke.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are involved in several developmental processes during embryonic development.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are released from the blastocyst, and are also expressed in the endometrium, and have critical roles in the stages of zona hatching, and implantation.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Dysregulated cytokine secretion in the aged population can lead to inflammaging, and render these individuals more vulnerable to age-related diseases like neurodegenerative diseases and type 2 diabetes.
[src:immunology/cytokine] A 2024 study found a positive correlation between plasma interleukin IL-2 and fatigue in patients with type 1 narcolepsy.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Autoantibodies against cytokines also plays a role in health and disease.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In 2020 neutralizing autoantibodies against type I interferons were reported in 10.2% of patients with life-threatening COVID-19.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In a subsequent follow-up study, researchers investigated that the prevalence of autoantibodies against type I interferons increases with age.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Only 0.17% of individuals under 70 years of age tested positive for these autoantibodies, compared with 4.2% among those aged 80 to 85 years.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Furthermore, autoantibodies against IFN-α/ω were detected in approximately 20% of patients over 80 years old with critical COVID-19.
[src:immunology/cytokine] A 2019 review was inconclusive as to whether cytokines play any definitive role in ME/CFS.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Adverse effects of cytokines have been linked to many disease states and conditions including schizophrenia, major depression, Alzheimer's disease, and cancer.
[src:immunology/cytokine] T regulatory cells (Tregs) and related-cytokines are effectively engaged in the process of tumor immune escape and functionally inhibit immune response against the tumor.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Forkhead box protein 3 (Foxp3) as a transcription factor is an essential molecular marker of Treg cells.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Foxp3 polymorphism (rs3761548) might be involved in cancer progression like gastric cancer through influencing Tregs function and the secretion of immunomodulatory cytokines such as IL-10, IL-35, and TGF-β.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Normal tissue integrity is preserved by feedback interactions between diverse cell types mediated by adhesion molecules and secreted cytokines; disruption of normal feedback mechanisms in cancer threatens tissue integrity.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Over-secretion of cytokines can trigger a dangerous cytokine storm syndrome.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokine storms may have been the cause of severe adverse events during a clinical trial of TGN1412.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokine storms are also suspected to have been the main cause of death in the 1918 "Spanish Flu" pandemic.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Deaths were weighted more heavily towards people with healthy immune systems, because of their ability to produce stronger immune responses, with dramatic increases in cytokine levels.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Another example of cytokine storm is seen in acute pancreatitis.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Cytokines are integral and implicated in all angles of the cascade, resulting in the systemic inflammatory response syndrome and multi-organ failure associated with this intra-abdominal catastrophe.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In the COVID-19 pandemic, some deaths from COVID-19 have been attributable to cytokine release storms.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Data suggest cytokine storms may be the source of extensive lung tissue damage and dysfunctional coagulation in COVID-19 infections.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Prenatal SARS-COV-2 infection in pregnant women is linked to developmental delays with high level of interferon-gamma in cord blood correlated with cognitive delays, while interleukin-6, IL-8, IL-17, and IL-1β were associated with motor delays.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Some cytokines have been developed into protein therapeutics using recombinant DNA technology.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Interferon-alpha, an interferon type I, was identified in 1957 as a protein that interfered with viral replication.
[src:immunology/cytokine] The activity of interferon-gamma (the sole member of the interferon type II class) was described in 1965; this was the first identified lymphocyte-derived mediator.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Macrophage migration inhibitory factor (MIF) was identified simultaneously in 1966 by John David and Barry Bloom.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In 1969, Dudley Dumonde proposed the term "lymphokine" to describe proteins secreted from lymphocytes and later, proteins derived from macrophages and monocytes in culture were called "monokines".
[src:immunology/cytokine] In 1974, pathologist Stanley Cohen, M.D.
[src:immunology/cytokine] This led to his proposal of the term cytokine.
[src:immunology/cytokine] In 1993, Ogawa described the early acting growth factors, intermediate acting growth factors and late acting growth factors.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Because cytokines often circulate in very low concentrations, highly sensitive assays are required for their measurement.
[src:immunology/cytokine] Various multiplex immunoassays have been developed to detect and quantify cytokines in plasma and other biofluids.
[src:immunology/cytokine] For example, the NULISAseq Inflammation Panel 250 is a multiplex assay designed to measure 250 low-abundance inflammation targets, including cytokines, chemokines, and growth factors (such as IL-1B, IL-6, IFN-γ, TNF, CXCL10, and CCL2).
[src:immunology/cytokine] According to the manufacturer, the assay utilizes NULISA technology to achieve attomolar sensitivity and a 12-log dynamic range from low sample volumes without the need for dilution.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The **immune system** is a network of biological systems that protects an organism from diseases.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] It detects and responds to a wide variety of pathogens, such as viruses, bacteria, and parasites, as well as cancer cells and foreign objects, such as wood splinters—distinguishing them from the organism's own healthy tissue.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Many species have two major subsystems of the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The innate immune system provides a preconfigured response to broad groups of situations and stimuli.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The adaptive immune system provides a tailored response to each stimulus by learning to recognize molecules it has previously encountered.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Both use molecules and cells to perform their functions.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Nearly all organisms have some kind of immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Bacteria have a rudimentary immune system in the form of enzymes that protect against viral infections.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Other basic immune mechanisms evolved in ancient plants and animals (eukaryotes) and remain in their modern descendants.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These mechanisms include phagocytosis, antimicrobial peptides called defensins, RNA interference, and the complement system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Jawed vertebrates, including humans, have a more sophisticated defense mechanism.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] For example, adaptive immunity provides the ability to adapt to recognize pathogens more efficiently (somatic hypermutation).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This process creates an immunological memory, resulting in an enhanced response against subsequent encounters with that same pathogen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This mechanism of adaptive immunity is the fundamental basis of vaccination.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Dysfunction of the immune system can cause autoimmune diseases, inflammatory diseases and cancer.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunodeficiency occurs when the immune system is less active than normal, resulting in recurring and life-threatening infections.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In humans, immunodeficiency can be the result of a genetic disease such as severe combined immunodeficiency, acquired conditions such as HIV/AIDS, or the use of immunosuppressive medication.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Autoimmunity results from a hyperactive immune system attacking normal tissues as if they were foreign organisms.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Common autoimmune diseases include Hashimoto's thyroiditis, rheumatoid arthritis, diabetes mellitus type 1, and systemic lupus erythematosus.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunology covers the study of all aspects of the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune system protects its host from infection with layered defenses of increasing specificity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Physical barriers prevent pathogens such as bacteria and viruses from entering the organism.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] If a pathogen breaches these barriers, the innate immune system provides an immediate, but non-specific response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Innate immune systems are found in all animals.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] If pathogens successfully evade the innate response, vertebrates possess a second layer of protection, the adaptive immune system, which is activated by the innate response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Here, the immune system adapts its response during an infection to improve its recognition of the pathogen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This improved response is then retained after the pathogen has been eliminated, in the form of an immunological memory, and allows the adaptive immune system to mount faster and stronger attacks each time this pathogen is encountered.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Both innate and adaptive immunity depend on the ability of the immune system to distinguish between self and non-self molecules.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In immunology, *self* molecules are components of an organism's body that can be distinguished from foreign substances by the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Conversely, *non-self* molecules are those recognized as foreign molecules.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] One class of non-self molecules are called antigens (originally named for being *anti*body *gen*erators) and are defined as substances that bind to specific immune receptors and elicit an immune response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Several barriers protect organisms from infection, including mechanical, chemical, and biological barriers.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The waxy cuticle of most leaves, the exoskeleton of insects, the shells and membranes of externally deposited eggs, and skin are examples of mechanical barriers that are the first line of defense against infection.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Organisms cannot be completely sealed from their environments, so systems act to protect body openings such as the lungs, intestines, and the genitourinary tract.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In the lungs, coughing and sneezing mechanically eject pathogens and other irritants from the respiratory tract.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The flushing action of tears and urine also mechanically expels pathogens, while mucus secreted by the respiratory and gastrointestinal tract serves to trap and entangle microorganisms.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Chemical barriers also protect against infection.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The skin and respiratory tract secrete antimicrobial peptides such as the β-defensins.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Enzymes such as lysozyme and phospholipase A2 in saliva, tears, and breast milk are also antibacterials.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Vaginal secretions serve as a chemical barrier following menarche, when they become slightly acidic, while semen contains defensins and zinc to kill pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In the stomach, gastric acid serves as a chemical defense against ingested pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Within the genitourinary and gastrointestinal tracts, commensal flora serve as biological barriers by competing with pathogenic bacteria for food and space and, in some cases, changing the conditions in their environment, such as pH or available iron.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] As a result, the probability that pathogens will reach sufficient numbers to cause illness is reduced.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Microorganisms or toxins that successfully enter an organism encounter the cells and mechanisms of the innate immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Innate immune defenses are non-specific, meaning these systems respond to pathogens in a generic way.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This system does not confer long-lasting immunity against a pathogen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The innate immune system is the dominant system of host defense in most organisms, and the only one in plants.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Cells in the innate immune system use pattern recognition receptors to recognize molecular structures that are produced by pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Cells in the innate immune system have pattern recognition receptors that detect internal infection or cell damage.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Three major classes of these "cytosolic" receptors are NOD–like receptors, RIG (retinoic acid-inducible gene)-like receptors, and cytosolic DNA sensors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Recognition of extracellular or endosomal PAMPs is mediated by transmembrane proteins known as toll-like receptors (TLRs).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] TLRs share a typical structural motif, the leucine rich repeats (LRRs), which give them a curved shape.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Toll-like receptors were first discovered in *Drosophila* and trigger the synthesis and secretion of cytokines and activation of other host defense programs that are necessary for both innate or adaptive immune responses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Ten toll-like receptors have been described in humans.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Some leukocytes (white blood cells) act like independent, single-celled organisms and are the second arm of the innate immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The innate leukocytes include the "professional" phagocytes (macrophages, neutrophils, and dendritic cells).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cells identify and eliminate pathogens, either by attacking larger pathogens through contact or by engulfing and then killing microorganisms.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The other cells involved in the innate response include innate lymphoid cells, mast cells, eosinophils, basophils, and natural killer cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Phagocytosis is an important feature of cellular innate immunity performed by cells called phagocytes that engulf pathogens or particles.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Phagocytes generally patrol the body searching for pathogens, but can be called to specific locations by cytokines.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Once a pathogen has been engulfed by a phagocyte, it becomes trapped in an intracellular vesicle called a phagosome, which subsequently fuses with another vesicle called a lysosome to form a phagolysosome.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The pathogen is killed by the activity of digestive enzymes or following a respiratory burst that releases free radicals into the phagolysosome.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Phagocytosis evolved as a means of acquiring nutrients, but this role was extended in phagocytes to include engulfment of pathogens as a defense mechanism.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Phagocytosis probably represents the oldest form of host defense, as phagocytes have been identified in both vertebrate and invertebrate animals.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Neutrophils and macrophages are phagocytes that travel throughout the body in pursuit of invading pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Neutrophils are normally found in the bloodstream and are the most abundant type of phagocyte, representing 50% to 60% of total circulating leukocytes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] During the acute phase of inflammation, neutrophils migrate toward the site of inflammation in a process called chemotaxis and are usually the first cells to arrive at the scene of infection.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Macrophages are versatile cells that reside within tissues and produce an array of chemicals including enzymes, complement proteins, and cytokines.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] They can also act as scavengers that rid the body of worn-out cells and other debris and as antigen-presenting cells (APCs) that activate the adaptive immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Dendritic cells are phagocytes in tissues that are in contact with the external environment; therefore, they are located mainly in the skin, nose, lungs, stomach, and intestines.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] They are named for their resemblance to neuronal dendrites, as both have many spine-like projections.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Dendritic cells serve as a link between the bodily tissues and the innate and adaptive immune systems, as they present antigens to T cells, one of the key cell types of the adaptive immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Granulocytes are leukocytes that have granules in their cytoplasm.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In this category are neutrophils, mast cells, basophils, and eosinophils.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Mast cells reside in connective tissues and mucous membranes and regulate the inflammatory response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] They are most often associated with allergy and anaphylaxis.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Basophils and eosinophils are related to neutrophils.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] They secrete chemical mediators that are involved in defending against parasites and play a role in allergic reactions, such as asthma.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Innate lymphoid cells (ILCs) are a group of innate immune cells that are derived from common lymphoid progenitor and belong to the lymphoid lineage.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cells are defined by the absence of antigen-specific B- or T-cell receptor (TCR) because of the lack of recombination activating gene.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] ILCs do not express myeloid or dendritic cell markers.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Natural killer cells (NK cells) are lymphocytes and a component of the innate immune system that does not directly attack invading microbes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Rather, NK cells destroy compromised host cells, such as tumor cells or virus-infected cells, recognizing such cells by a condition known as "missing self".
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This term describes cells with low levels of a cell-surface marker called MHC I (major histocompatibility complex)—a situation that can arise in viral infections of host cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Normal body cells are not recognized and attacked by NK cells because they express intact self MHC antigens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Those MHC antigens are recognized by killer cell immunoglobulin receptors, which essentially put the brakes on NK cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Inflammation is one of the first responses of the immune system to infection.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The symptoms of inflammation are redness, swelling, heat, and pain, which are caused by increased blood flow into tissue.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Inflammation is produced by eicosanoids and cytokines, which are released by injured or infected cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Eicosanoids include prostaglandins that produce fever and the dilation of blood vessels associated with inflammation and leukotrienes that attract certain white blood cells (leukocytes).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Common cytokines include interleukins that are responsible for communication between white blood cells; chemokines that promote chemotaxis; and interferons that have antiviral effects, such as shutting down protein synthesis in the host cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Growth factors and cytotoxic factors may also be released.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cytokines and other chemicals recruit immune cells to the site of infection and promote the healing of any damaged tissue following the removal of pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The complement system is a biochemical cascade that attacks the surfaces of foreign cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] It contains over 20 different proteins and is named for its ability to "complement" the killing of pathogens by antibodies.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Complement is the major humoral component of the innate immune response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Many species have complement systems, including non-mammals like plants, fish, and some invertebrates.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In humans, this response is activated by complement binding to antibodies that have attached to these microbes or the binding of complement proteins to carbohydrates on the surfaces of microbes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This recognition signal triggers a rapid killing response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The speed of the response is a result of signal amplification that occurs after sequential proteolytic activation of complement molecules, which are also proteases.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] After complement proteins initially bind to the microbe, they activate their protease activity, which in turn activates other complement proteases, and so on.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This produces a catalytic cascade that amplifies the initial signal by controlled positive feedback.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The cascade results in the production of peptides that attract immune cells, increase vascular permeability, and opsonize (coat) the surface of a pathogen, marking it for destruction.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This deposition of complement can also kill cells directly by disrupting their plasma membrane via the formation of a membrane attack complex.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The adaptive immune system evolved in early vertebrates and allows for a stronger immune response as well as immunological memory, where each pathogen is "remembered" by a signature antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The adaptive immune response is antigen-specific and requires the recognition of specific "non-self" antigens during a process called antigen presentation.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Antigen specificity allows for the generation of responses that are tailored to specific pathogens or pathogen-infected cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The ability to mount these tailored responses is maintained in the body by "memory cells".
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Should a pathogen infect the body more than once, these specific memory cells are used to quickly eliminate it.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] On the other hand, the immune system shows immune tolerance for "self-proteins".
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The cells of the adaptive immune system are special types of leukocytes, called lymphocytes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] B cells and T cells are the major types of lymphocytes and are derived from hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] B cells are involved in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are involved in cell-mediated immune response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Killer T cells only recognize antigens coupled to Class I MHC molecules, while helper T cells and regulatory T cells only recognize antigens coupled to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These two mechanisms of antigen presentation reflect the different roles of the two types of T cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] A third, minor subtype are the γδ T cells that recognize intact antigens that are not bound to MHC receptors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The double-positive T cells are exposed to a wide variety of self-antigens in the thymus, in which iodine is necessary for its thymus development and activity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In contrast, the B cell antigen-specific receptor is an antibody molecule on the B cell surface and recognizes native (unprocessed) antigen without any need for antigen processing.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Such antigens may be large molecules found on the surfaces of pathogens, but can also be small haptens (such as penicillin) attached to carrier molecule.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Each lineage of B cell expresses a different antibody, so the complete set of B cell antigen receptors represent all the antibodies that the body can manufacture.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] When B or T cells encounter their related antigens they multiply and many "clones" of the cells are produced that target the same antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Both B cells and T cells carry receptor molecules that recognize specific targets.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] T cells recognize a "non-self" target, such as a pathogen, only after antigens (small fragments of the pathogen) have been processed and presented in combination with a "self" receptor called a major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecule.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] There are two major subtypes of T cells: the killer T cell and the helper T cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In addition there are regulatory T cells which have a role in modulating immune response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Killer T cells are a sub-group of T cells that kill cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] As with B cells, each type of T cell recognizes a different antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Killer T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor binds to this specific antigen in a complex with the MHC Class I receptor of another cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Recognition of this MHC:antigen complex is aided by a co-receptor on the T cell, called CD8.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The T cell then travels throughout the body in search of cells where the MHC I receptors bear this antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] When an activated T cell contacts such cells, it releases cytotoxins, such as perforin, which form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions, water and toxins to enter.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The entry of another toxin called granulysin (a protease) induces the target cell to undergo apoptosis.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] T cell killing of host cells is particularly important in preventing the replication of viruses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] T cell activation is tightly controlled and generally requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T cells (see below).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Helper T cells regulate both the innate and adaptive immune responses and help determine which immune responses the body makes to a particular pathogen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cells have no cytotoxic activity and do not kill infected cells or clear pathogens directly.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] They instead control the immune response by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Helper T cells express T cell receptors that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The MHC:antigen complex is also recognized by the helper cell's CD4 co-receptor, which recruits molecules inside the T cell (such as Lck) that are responsible for the T cell's activation.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Helper T cell activation also requires longer duration of engagement with an antigen-presenting cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The activation of a resting helper T cell causes it to release cytokines that influence the activity of many cell types.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Cytokine signals produced by helper T cells enhance the microbicidal function of macrophages and the activity of killer T cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In addition, helper T cell activation causes an upregulation of molecules expressed on the T cell's surface, such as CD40 ligand (also called CD154), which provide extra stimulatory signals typically required to activate antibody-producing B cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T-cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ (αβ) T cells and share the characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and NK cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The conditions that produce responses from γδ T cells are not fully understood.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells straddle the border between innate and adaptive immunity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] On one hand, γδ T cells are a component of adaptive immunity as they rearrange TCR genes to produce receptor diversity and can also develop a memory phenotype.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] On the other hand, the various subsets are also part of the innate immune system, as restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as pattern recognition receptors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] For example, large numbers of human Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted Vδ1+ T cells in epithelia respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] A B cell identifies pathogens when antibodies on its surface bind to a specific foreign antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This antigen/antibody complex is taken up by the B cell and processed by proteolysis into peptides.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The B cell then displays these antigenic peptides on its surface MHC class II molecules.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This combination of MHC and antigen attracts a matching helper T cell, which releases lymphokines and activates the B cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] As the activated B cell then begins to divide, its offspring (plasma cells) secrete millions of copies of the antibody that recognizes this antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These antibodies circulate in blood plasma and lymph, bind to pathogens expressing the antigen and mark them for destruction by complement activation or for uptake and destruction by phagocytes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Antibodies can also neutralize challenges directly, by binding to bacterial toxins or by interfering with the receptors that viruses and bacteria use to infect cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Newborn infants have no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] During pregnancy, a particular type of antibody, called IgG, is transported from mother to baby directly through the placenta, so human babies have high levels of antibodies even at birth, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Breast milk or colostrum also contains antibodies that are transferred to the gut of the infant and protect against bacterial infections until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies—it only borrows them.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This passive immunity is usually short-term, lasting from a few days up to several months.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In medicine, protective passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] When B cells and T cells are activated and begin to replicate, some of their offspring become long-lived memory cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Throughout the lifetime of an animal, these memory cells remember each specific pathogen encountered and can mount a strong response if the pathogen is detected again.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] T-cells recognize pathogens by small protein-based infection signals, called antigens, that bind directly to T-cell surface receptors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] B-cells use the protein, immunoglobulin, to recognize pathogens by their antigens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This is "adaptive" because it occurs during the lifetime of an individual as an adaptation to infection with that pathogen and prepares the immune system for future challenges.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunological memory can be in the form of either passive short-term memory or active long-term memory.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune system is involved in many aspects of physiological regulation in the body.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune system interacts intimately with other systems, such as the endocrine and the nervous systems.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune system also plays a crucial role in embryogenesis (development of the embryo), as well as in tissue repair and regeneration.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Hormones can act as immunomodulators, altering the sensitivity of the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] For example, female sex hormones are known immunostimulators of both adaptive and innate immune responses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Some autoimmune diseases such as lupus erythematosus strike women preferentially, and their onset often coincides with puberty.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] By contrast, male sex hormones such as testosterone seem to be immunosuppressive.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Other hormones appear to regulate the immune system as well, most notably prolactin, growth hormone and vitamin D.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune system is affected by sleep and rest, and sleep deprivation is detrimental to immune function.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Complex feedback loops involving cytokines, such as interleukin-1 and tumor necrosis factor-α produced in response to infection, appear to also play a role in the regulation of non-rapid eye movement (NREM) sleep.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Thus the immune response to infection may result in changes to the sleep cycle, including an increase in slow-wave sleep relative to rapid eye movement (REM) sleep.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In people with sleep deprivation, active immunizations may have a diminished effect and may result in lower antibody production, and a lower immune response, than would be noted in a well-rested individual.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Additionally, proteins such as NFIL3, which have been shown to be closely intertwined with both T-cell differentiation and circadian rhythms, can be affected through the disturbance of natural light and dark cycles through instances of sleep deprivation.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These disruptions can lead to an increase in chronic conditions such as heart disease, chronic pain, and asthma.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In addition to the negative consequences of sleep deprivation, sleep and the intertwined circadian system have been shown to have strong regulatory effects on immunological functions affecting both innate and adaptive immunity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] First, during the early slow-wave-sleep stage, a sudden drop in blood levels of cortisol, epinephrine, and norepinephrine causes increased blood levels of the hormones leptin, pituitary growth hormone, and prolactin.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These signals induce a pro-inflammatory state through the production of the pro-inflammatory cytokines interleukin-1, interleukin-12, TNF-alpha and IFN-gamma.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cytokines then stimulate immune functions such as immune cell activation, proliferation, and differentiation.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] During this time of a slowly evolving adaptive immune response, there is a peak in undifferentiated or less differentiated cells, like naïve and central memory T cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This is also thought to support the formation of long-lasting immune memory through the initiation of Th1 immune responses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] During wake periods, differentiated effector cells, such as cytotoxic natural killer cells and CD45RA+ cytotoxic T lymphocytes, peak in numbers.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Anti-inflammatory molecules, such as cortisol and catecholamines, also peak during awake active times.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Inflammation can cause oxidative stress and the presence of melatonin during sleep times could counteract free radical production during this time.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Physical exercise has a positive effect on the immune system and depending on the frequency and intensity, the pathogenic effects of diseases caused by bacteria and viruses are moderated.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immediately after intense exercise there is a transient immunodepression, where the number of circulating lymphocytes decreases and antibody production declines.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This may give rise to a window of opportunity for infection and reactivation of latent virus infections, but the evidence is inconclusive.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] During exercise there is an increase in circulating white blood cells of all types.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This is caused by the frictional force of blood flowing on the endothelial cell surface and catecholamines affecting β-adrenergic receptors (βARs).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The number of neutrophils in the blood increases and remains raised for up to six hours and immature forms are present.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Although the increase in neutrophils ("neutrophilia") is similar to that seen during bacterial infections, after exercise the cell population returns to normal by around 24 hours.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The number of circulating lymphocytes (mainly natural killer cells) decreases during intense exercise but returns to normal after 4 to 6 hours.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Although up to 2% of the cells die most migrate from the blood to the tissues, mainly the intestines and lungs, where pathogens are most likely to be encountered.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Some monocytes leave the blood circulation and migrate to the muscles where they differentiate and become macrophages.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cells differentiate into two types: proliferative macrophages, which are responsible for increasing the number of stem cells and restorative macrophages, which are involved their maturing to muscle cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune system, particularly the innate component, plays a decisive role in tissue repair after an insult.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Key actors include macrophages and neutrophils, but other cellular actors, including γδ T cells, innate lymphoid cells (ILCs), and regulatory T cells (Tregs), are also important.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The plasticity of immune cells and the balance between pro-inflammatory and anti-inflammatory signals are crucial aspects of efficient tissue repair.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immune components and pathways are involved in regeneration as well, for example in amphibians such as in axolotl limb regeneration.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] According to one hypothesis, organisms that can regenerate (*e.g.*, axolotls) could be less immunocompetent than organisms that cannot regenerate.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Failures of host defense occur and fall into three broad categories: immunodeficiencies, autoimmunity, and hypersensitivities.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunodeficiencies occur when one or more of the components of the immune system are inactive.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The ability of the immune system to respond to pathogens is diminished in both the young and the elderly, with immune responses beginning to decline at around 50 years of age due to immunosenescence.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In developed countries, obesity, alcoholism, and drug use are common causes of poor immune function, while malnutrition is the most common cause of immunodeficiency in developing countries.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Diets lacking sufficient protein are associated with impaired cell-mediated immunity, complement activity, phagocyte function, IgA antibody concentrations, and cytokine production.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Additionally, the loss of the thymus at an early age through genetic mutation or surgical removal results in severe immunodeficiency and a high susceptibility to infection.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunodeficiencies can also be inherited or 'acquired'.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Severe combined immunodeficiency is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the disturbed development of functional T cells and B cells caused by numerous genetic mutations.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Chronic granulomatous disease, where phagocytes have a reduced ability to destroy pathogens, is an example of an inherited, or congenital, immunodeficiency.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] AIDS and some types of cancer cause acquired immunodeficiency.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Overactive immune responses form the other end of immune dysfunction, particularly the autoimmune diseases.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Here, the immune system fails to properly distinguish between self and non-self, and attacks part of the body.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Under normal circumstances, many T cells and antibodies react with "self" peptides.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] One of the functions of specialized cells (located in the thymus and bone marrow) is to present young lymphocytes with self antigens produced throughout the body and to eliminate those cells that recognize self-antigens, preventing autoimmunity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Hypersensitivity is an immune response that damages the body's own tissues.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] It is divided into four classes (Type I – IV) based on the mechanisms involved and the time course of the hypersensitive reaction.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Type I hypersensitivity is an immediate or anaphylactic reaction, often associated with allergy.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Symptoms can range from mild discomfort to death.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Type I hypersensitivity is mediated by IgE, which triggers degranulation of mast cells and basophils when cross-linked by antigen.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Type II hypersensitivity occurs when antibodies bind to antigens on the individual's own cells, marking them for destruction.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This is also called antibody-dependent (or cytotoxic) hypersensitivity, and is mediated by IgG and IgM antibodies.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immune complexes (aggregations of antigens, complement proteins, and IgG and IgM antibodies) deposited in various tissues trigger Type III hypersensitivity reactions.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Type IV hypersensitivity (also known as cell-mediated or *delayed type hypersensitivity*) usually takes between two and three days to develop.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Type IV reactions are involved in many autoimmune and infectious diseases, but may also involve contact dermatitis.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These reactions are mediated by T cells, monocytes, and macrophages.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Inflammation is one of the first responses of the immune system to infection, but it can appear without known cause.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Eicosanoids include prostaglandins that produce fever and the dilation of blood vessels associated with inflammation, and leukotrienes that attract certain white blood cells (leukocytes).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Common cytokines include interleukins that are responsible for communication between white blood cells; chemokines that promote chemotaxis; and interferons that have anti-viral effects, such as shutting down protein synthesis in the host cell.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] These cytokines and other chemicals recruit immune cells to the site of infection and promote healing of any damaged tissue following the removal of pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The immune response can be manipulated to suppress unwanted responses resulting from autoimmunity, allergy, and transplant rejection, and to stimulate protective responses against pathogens that largely elude the immune system (see immunization) or cancer.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunosuppressive drugs are used to control autoimmune disorders or inflammation when excessive tissue damage occurs, and to prevent rejection after an organ transplant.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Anti-inflammatory drugs are often used to control the effects of inflammation.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Glucocorticoids are the most powerful of these drugs and can have many undesirable side effects, such as central obesity, hyperglycemia, and osteoporosis.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Lower doses of anti-inflammatory drugs are often used in conjunction with cytotoxic or immunosuppressive drugs such as methotrexate or azathioprine.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Cytotoxic drugs inhibit the immune response by killing dividing cells such as activated T cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This killing is indiscriminate and other constantly dividing cells and their organs are affected, which causes toxic side effects.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunosuppressive drugs such as cyclosporin prevent T cells from responding to signals correctly by inhibiting signal transduction pathways.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Claims made by marketers of various products and alternative health providers, such as chiropractors, homeopaths, and acupuncturists to be able to stimulate or "boost" the immune system generally lack meaningful explanation and evidence of effectiveness.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Long-term *active* memory is acquired following infection by activation of B and T cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Active immunity can also be generated artificially, through vaccination.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The principle behind vaccination (also called immunization) is to introduce an antigen from a pathogen to stimulate the immune system and develop specific immunity against that particular pathogen without causing disease associated with that organism.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This deliberate induction of an immune response is successful because it exploits the natural specificity of the immune system, as well as its inducibility.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] With infectious disease remaining one of the leading causes of death in the human population, vaccination represents the most effective manipulation of the immune system mankind has developed.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Many vaccines are based on acellular components of micro-organisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Since many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce the adaptive response, most bacterial vaccines are provided with additional adjuvants that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system and maximize immunogenicity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Another important role of the immune system is to identify and eliminate tumors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The *transformed cells* of tumors express antigens that are not found on normal cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] To the immune system, these antigens appear foreign, and their presence causes immune cells to attack the transformed tumor cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] One example is an enzyme called tyrosinase that, when expressed at high levels, transforms certain skin cells (for example, melanocytes) into tumors called melanomas.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] A third possible source of tumor antigens are proteins normally important for regulating cell growth and survival, that commonly mutate into cancer inducing molecules called oncogenes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The main response of the immune system to tumors is to destroy the abnormal cells using killer T cells, sometimes with the assistance of helper T cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Tumor antigens are presented on MHC class I molecules in a similar way to viral antigens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This allows killer T cells to recognize the tumor cell as abnormal.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] NK cells also kill tumorous cells in a similar way, especially if the tumor cells have fewer MHC class I molecules on their surface than normal; this is a common phenomenon with tumors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Sometimes antibodies are generated against tumor cells allowing for their destruction by the complement system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Some tumors evade the immune system and go on to become cancers.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Tumor cells often have a reduced number of MHC class I molecules on their surface, thus avoiding detection by killer T cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Some tumor cells also release products that inhibit the immune response; for example by secreting the cytokine TGF-β, which suppresses the activity of macrophages and lymphocytes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In addition, immunological tolerance may develop against tumor antigens, so the immune system no longer attacks the tumor cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Paradoxically, macrophages can promote tumor growth when tumor cells send out cytokines that attract macrophages, which then generate cytokines and growth factors such as tumor-necrosis factor alpha that nurture tumor development or promote stem-cell-like plasticity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In addition, a combination of hypoxia in the tumor and a cytokine produced by macrophages induces tumor cells to decrease production of a protein that blocks metastasis and thereby assists spread of cancer cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Anti-tumor M1 macrophages are recruited in early phases to tumor development but are progressively differentiated to M2 with pro-tumor effect, an immunosuppressor switch.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The hypoxia reduces the cytokine production for the anti-tumor response and progressively macrophages acquire pro-tumor M2 functions driven by the tumor microenvironment, including IL-4 and IL-10.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Cancer immunotherapy covers the medical ways to stimulate the immune system to attack cancer tumors.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Some drugs can cause a neutralizing immune response, meaning that the immune system produces neutralizing antibodies that counteract the action of the drugs, particularly if the drugs are administered repeatedly, or in larger doses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] This limits the effectiveness of drugs based on larger peptides and proteins (which are typically larger than 6000 Da).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] In some cases, the drug itself is not immunogenic, but may be co-administered with an immunogenic compound, as is sometimes the case for Taxol.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Computational methods have been developed to predict the immunogenicity of peptides and proteins, which are particularly useful in designing therapeutic antibodies, assessing likely virulence of mutations in viral coat particles, and validation of proposed peptide-based drug treatments.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] A publicly accessible database has been established for the cataloguing of epitopes from pathogens known to be recognizable by B cells.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] The emerging field of bioinformatics-based studies of immunogenicity is referred to as *immunoinformatics*.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p01] Immunoproteomics is the study of large sets of proteins (proteomics) involved in the immune response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] It is likely that a multicomponent, adaptive immune system arose with the first vertebrates, as invertebrates do not generate lymphocytes or an antibody-based humoral response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Immune systems evolved in deuterostomes as shown in the cladogram.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Many species, however, use mechanisms that appear to be precursors of these aspects of vertebrate immunity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Immune systems appear even in the structurally simplest forms of life, with bacteria using a unique defense mechanism, called the restriction modification system to protect themselves from viral pathogens, called bacteriophages.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Prokaryotes (bacteria and archaea) also possess acquired immunity, through a system that uses CRISPR sequences to retain fragments of the genomes of phage that they have come into contact with in the past, which allows them to block virus replication through a form of RNA interference.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Prokaryotes also possess other defense mechanisms.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Offensive elements of the immune systems are also present in unicellular eukaryotes, but studies of their roles in defense are few.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Pattern recognition receptors are proteins used by nearly all organisms to identify molecules associated with pathogens.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Antimicrobial peptides called defensins are an evolutionarily conserved component of the innate immune response found in all animals and plants, and represent the main form of invertebrate systemic immunity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] The complement system and phagocytic cells are also used by most forms of invertebrate life.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Ribonucleases and the RNA interference pathway are conserved across all eukaryotes, and are thought to play a role in the immune response to viruses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Unlike animals, plants lack phagocytic cells, but many plant immune responses involve systemic chemical signals that are sent through a plant.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Individual plant cells respond to molecules associated with pathogens known as pathogen-associated molecular patterns or PAMPs.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] When a part of a plant becomes infected, the plant produces a localized hypersensitive response, whereby cells at the site of infection undergo rapid apoptosis to prevent the spread of the disease to other parts of the plant.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Systemic acquired resistance is a type of defensive response used by plants that renders the entire plant resistant to a particular infectious agent.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] RNA silencing mechanisms are particularly important in this systemic response as they can block virus replication.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Evolution of the adaptive immune system occurred in an ancestor of the jawed vertebrates.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Many of the classical molecules of the adaptive immune system (for example, immunoglobulins and T-cell receptors) exist only in jawed vertebrates.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] A distinct lymphocyte-derived molecule has been discovered in primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] These animals possess a large array of molecules called Variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] The success of any pathogen depends on its ability to elude host immune responses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Therefore, pathogens evolved several methods that allow them to successfully infect a host, while evading detection or destruction by the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Bacteria often overcome physical barriers by secreting enzymes that digest the barrier, for example, by using a type II secretion system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Alternatively, using a type III secretion system, they may insert a hollow tube into the host cell, providing a direct route for proteins to move from the pathogen to the host.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] These proteins are often used to shut down host defenses.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] An evasion strategy used by several pathogens to avoid the innate immune system is to hide within the cells of their host (also called intracellular pathogenesis).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Here, a pathogen spends most of its life-cycle inside host cells, where it is shielded from direct contact with immune cells, antibodies and complement.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Some examples of intracellular pathogens include viruses, the food poisoning bacterium *Salmonella* and the eukaryotic parasites that cause malaria (*Plasmodium spp.*) and leishmaniasis (*Leishmania spp.*).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Other bacteria, such as *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, live inside a protective capsule that prevents lysis by complement.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Many pathogens secrete compounds that diminish or misdirect the host's immune response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Some bacteria form biofilms to protect themselves from the cells and proteins of the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Such biofilms are present in many successful infections, such as the chronic *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and *Burkholderia cenocepacia* infections characteristic of cystic fibrosis.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Other bacteria generate surface proteins that bind to antibodies, rendering them ineffective; examples include *Streptococcus* (protein G), *Staphylococcus aureus* (protein A), and *Peptostreptococcus magnus* (protein L).
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] The mechanisms used to evade the adaptive immune system are more complicated.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] The simplest approach is to rapidly change non-essential epitopes (amino acids and/or sugars) on the surface of the pathogen, while keeping essential epitopes concealed.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] An example is HIV, which mutates rapidly, so the proteins on its viral envelope that are essential for entry into its host target cell are constantly changing.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] These frequent changes in antigens may explain the failures of vaccines directed at this virus.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] The parasite *Trypanosoma brucei* uses a similar strategy, constantly switching one type of surface protein for another, allowing it to stay one step ahead of the antibody response.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Masking antigens with host molecules is another common strategy for avoiding detection by the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] In HIV, the envelope that covers the virion is formed from the outermost membrane of the host cell; such "self-cloaked" viruses make it difficult for the immune system to identify them as "non-self" structures.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Immunology is a science that examines the structure and function of the immune system.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] It originates from medicine and early studies on the causes of immunity to disease.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] The earliest known reference to immunity was during the plague of Athens in 430 BC.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Thucydides noted that people who had recovered from a previous bout of the disease could nurse the sick without contracting the illness a second time.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] In the 18th century, Pierre-Louis Moreau de Maupertuis experimented with scorpion venom and observed that certain dogs and mice were immune to this venom.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] In the 10th century, Persian physician al-Razi (also known as Rhazes) wrote the first recorded theory of acquired immunity, noting that a smallpox bout protected its survivors from future infections.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Although he explained the immunity in terms of "excess moisture" being expelled from the blood—therefore preventing a second occurrence of the disease—this theory explained many observations about smallpox known during this time.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] These and other observations of acquired immunity were later exploited by Louis Pasteur in his development of vaccination and his proposed germ theory of disease.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Pasteur's theory was in direct opposition to contemporary theories of disease, such as the miasma theory.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] It was not until Robert Koch's 1891 proofs, for which he was awarded a Nobel Prize in 1905, that microorganisms were confirmed as the cause of infectious disease.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Viruses were confirmed as human pathogens in 1901, with the discovery of the yellow fever virus by Walter Reed.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Immunology made a great advance towards the end of the 19th century, through rapid developments in the study of humoral immunity and cellular immunity.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] In 1974, Niels Kaj Jerne developed the immune network theory; he shared a Nobel Prize in 1984 with Georges J.
[src:immunology/immune-system-p02] Köhler and César Milstein for theories related to the immune system.
[src:immunology/immunology] Immunology has applications in numerous disciplines of medicine, particularly in the fields of organ transplantation, oncology, rheumatology, virology, bacteriology, parasitology, psychiatry, and dermatology.
[src:immunology/immunology] The term was coined by Russian biologist Ilya Ilyich Mechnikov, who advanced studies on immunology and received the Nobel Prize for his work in 1908 with Paul Ehrlich "in recognition of their work on immunity".
[src:immunology/immunology] He pinned small thorns into starfish larvae and noticed unusual cells surrounding the thorns.
[src:immunology/immunology] This was the active response of the body trying to maintain its integrity.
[src:immunology/immunology] It was Mechnikov who first observed the phenomenon of phagocytosis, in which the body defends itself against a foreign body.
[src:immunology/immunology] Ehrlich accustomed mice to the poisonous ricin and abrin.
[src:immunology/immunology] After feeding them with small but increasing dosages of ricin he ascertained that they had become "ricin-proof".
[src:immunology/immunology] Ehrlich interpreted this as immunization and observed that it was abruptly initiated after a few days and was still in existence after several months.
[src:immunology/immunology] Prior to the designation of immunity, from the etymological root *immunis*, which is Latin for 'exempt', early physicians characterized organs that would later be proven as essential components of the immune system.
[src:immunology/immunology] The important lymphoid organs of the immune system are the thymus, bone marrow, and chief lymphatic tissues such as spleen, tonsils, lymph vessels, lymph nodes, adenoids, and liver.
[src:immunology/immunology] However, many components of the immune system are cellular in nature, and not associated with specific organs, but rather embedded or circulating in various tissues located throughout the body.
[src:immunology/immunology] Classical immunology ties in with the fields of epidemiology and medicine.
[src:immunology/immunology] It studies the relationship between the body systems, pathogens, and immunity.
[src:immunology/immunology] The earliest written mention of immunity can be traced back to the plague of Athens in 430 BCE.
[src:immunology/immunology] Many other ancient societies have references to this phenomenon, but it was not until the 19th and 20th centuries before the concept developed into scientific theory.
[src:immunology/immunology] The study of the molecular and cellular components that comprise the immune system, including their function and interaction, is the central science of immunology.
[src:immunology/immunology] The immune system has been divided into a more primitive innate immune system and, in vertebrates, an acquired or adaptive immune system.
[src:immunology/immunology] The latter is further divided into humoral (or antibody) and cell-mediated components.
[src:immunology/immunology] The immune system has the capability of self and non-self-recognition.
[src:immunology/immunology] An antigen is a substance that ignites the immune response.
[src:immunology/immunology] The cells involved in recognizing the antigen are Lymphocytes.
[src:immunology/immunology] Once they recognize, they secrete antibodies.
[src:immunology/immunology] Antibodies are proteins that neutralize the disease-causing microorganisms.
[src:immunology/immunology] Antibodies do not directly kill pathogens, but instead, identify antigens as targets for destruction by other immune cells such as phagocytes or NK cells.
[src:immunology/immunology] The (antibody) response is defined as the interaction between antibodies and antigens.
[src:immunology/immunology] Antibodies are specific proteins released from a certain class of immune cells known as B lymphocytes, while antigens are defined as anything that elicits the generation of antibodies (**anti**body **gen**erators).
[src:immunology/immunology] Immunology rests on an understanding of the properties of these two biological entities and the cellular response to both.
[src:immunology/immunology] It is now getting clear that the immune responses contribute to the development of many common disorders not traditionally viewed as immunologic, including metabolic, cardiovascular, cancer, and neurodegenerative conditions like Alzheimer's disease.
[src:immunology/immunology] Besides, there are direct implications of the immune system in the infectious diseases (tuberculosis, malaria, hepatitis, pneumonia, dysentery, and helminth infestations) as well.
[src:immunology/immunology] Hence, research in the field of immunology is of prime importance for the advancements in the fields of modern medicine, biomedical research, and biotechnology.
[src:immunology/immunology] The specificity of the bond between antibody and antigen has made the antibody an excellent tool for the detection of substances by a variety of diagnostic techniques.
[src:immunology/immunology] Antibodies specific for a desired antigen can be conjugated with an isotopic (radio) or fluorescent label or with a color-forming enzyme in order to detect it.
[src:immunology/immunology] However, the similarity between some antigens can lead to false positives and other errors in such tests by antibodies cross-reacting with antigens that are not exact matches.
[src:immunology/immunology] The use of immune system components or antigens to treat a disease or disorder is known as immunotherapy.
[src:immunology/immunology] Immunotherapy is most commonly used to treat allergies, autoimmune disorders such as Crohn's disease, Hashimoto's thyroiditis and rheumatoid arthritis, and certain cancers.
[src:immunology/immunology] Immunotherapy is also often used for patients who are immunosuppressed (such as those with HIV) and people with other immune deficiencies.
[src:immunology/immunology] This includes regulating factors such as IL-2, IL-10, GM-CSF B, IFN-α.
[src:immunology/immunology] Clinical immunology is the study of diseases caused by disorders of the immune system (failure, aberrant action, and malignant growth of the cellular elements of the system).
[src:immunology/immunology] It also involves diseases of other systems, where immune reactions play a part in the pathology and clinical features.
[src:immunology/immunology] Other immune system disorders include various hypersensitivities (such as in asthma and other allergies) that respond inappropriately to otherwise harmless compounds.
[src:immunology/immunology] The most well-known disease that affects the immune system itself is AIDS, an immunodeficiency characterized by the suppression of CD4+ ("helper") T cells, dendritic cells and macrophages by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:immunology/immunology] Clinical immunologists also study ways to prevent the immune system's attempts to destroy allografts (transplant rejection).
[src:immunology/immunology] Clinical immunology and allergy is usually a subspecialty of internal medicine or pediatrics.
[src:immunology/immunology] Fellows in Clinical Immunology are typically exposed to many of the different aspects of the specialty and treat allergic conditions, primary immunodeficiencies and systemic autoimmune and autoinflammatory conditions.
[src:immunology/immunology] As part of their training fellows may do additional rotations in rheumatology, pulmonology, otorhinolaryngology, dermatology and the immunologic lab.
[src:immunology/immunology] When health conditions worsen to emergency status, portions of immune system organs, including the thymus, spleen, bone marrow, lymph nodes, and other lymphatic tissues, can be surgically excised for examination while patients are still alive.
[src:immunology/immunology] Immunology is strongly experimental in everyday practice but is also characterized by an ongoing theoretical attitude.
[src:immunology/immunology] Many theories have been suggested in immunology from the end of the nineteenth century up to the present time.
[src:immunology/immunology] The end of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th century saw a battle between "cellular" and "humoral" theories of immunity.
[src:immunology/immunology] According to the cellular theory of immunity, represented in particular by Elie Metchnikoff, it was cells – more precisely, phagocytes – that were responsible for immune responses.
[src:immunology/immunology] In contrast, the humoral theory of immunity, held by Robert Koch and Emil von Behring, among others, stated that the active immune agents were soluble components (molecules) found in the organism's "humors" rather than its cells.
[src:immunology/immunology] In the mid-1950s, Macfarlane Burnet, inspired by a suggestion made by Niels Jerne, formulated the clonal selection theory (CST) of immunity.
[src:immunology/immunology] The theory was later modified to reflect new discoveries regarding histocompatibility or the complex "two-signal" activation of T cells.
[src:immunology/immunology] The self/nonself theory of immunity and the self/nonself vocabulary have been criticized, but remain very influential.
[src:immunology/immunology] More recently, several theoretical frameworks have been suggested in immunology, including "autopoietic" views, "cognitive immune" views, the "danger model" (or "danger theory"), and the "discontinuity" theory.
[src:immunology/immunology] The danger model, suggested by Polly Matzinger and colleagues, has been very influential, arousing many comments and discussions.
[src:immunology/immunology] The body's capability to react to antigens depends on a person's age, antigen type, maternal factors and the area where the antigen is presented.
[src:immunology/immunology] Neonates are said to be in a state of physiological immunodeficiency, because both their innate and adaptive immunological responses are greatly suppressed.
[src:immunology/immunology] Once born, a child's immune system responds favorably to protein antigens while not as well to glycoproteins and polysaccharides.
[src:immunology/immunology] In fact, many of the infections acquired by neonates are caused by low virulence organisms like *Staphylococcus* and *Pseudomonas*.
[src:immunology/immunology] In neonates, opsonic activity and the ability to activate the complement cascade is very limited.
[src:immunology/immunology] For example, the mean level of C3 in a newborn is approximately 65% of that found in the adult.
[src:immunology/immunology] Phagocytic activity is also greatly impaired in newborns.
[src:immunology/immunology] This is due to lower opsonic activity, as well as diminished up-regulation of integrin and selectin receptors, which limit the ability of neutrophils to interact with adhesion molecules in the endothelium.
[src:immunology/immunology] Their monocytes are slow and have a reduced ATP production, which also limits the newborn's phagocytic activity.
[src:immunology/immunology] Although, the number of total lymphocytes is significantly higher than in adults, the cellular and humoral immunity is also impaired.
[src:immunology/immunology] Antigen-presenting cells in newborns have a reduced capability to activate T cells.
[src:immunology/immunology] Also, T cells of a newborn proliferate poorly and produce very small amounts of cytokines like IL-2, IL-4, IL-5, IL-12, and IFN-g which limits their capacity to activate the humoral response as well as the phagocitic activity of macrophage.
[src:immunology/immunology] B cells develop early during gestation but are not fully active.
[src:immunology/immunology] Maternal factors also play a role in the body's immune response.
[src:immunology/immunology] At birth, most of the immunoglobulin present is maternal IgG.
[src:immunology/immunology] These antibodies are transferred from the placenta to the fetus using the FcRn (neonatal Fc receptor).
[src:immunology/immunology] Because IgM, IgD, IgE and IgA do not cross the placenta, they are almost undetectable at birth.
[src:immunology/immunology] These passively-acquired antibodies can protect the newborn for up to 18 months, but their response is usually short-lived and of low affinity.
[src:immunology/immunology] These antibodies can also produce a negative response.
[src:immunology/immunology] If a child is exposed to the antibody for a particular antigen before being exposed to the antigen itself then the child will produce a dampened response.
[src:immunology/immunology] Passively acquired maternal antibodies can suppress the antibody response to active immunization.
[src:immunology/immunology] Similarly, the response of T-cells to vaccination differs in children compared to adults, and vaccines that induce Th1 responses in adults do not readily elicit these same responses in neonates.
[src:immunology/immunology] Between six and nine months after birth, a child's immune system begins to respond more strongly to glycoproteins, but there is usually no marked improvement in their response to polysaccharides until they are at least one year old.
[src:immunology/immunology] This can be the reason for distinct time frames found in vaccination schedules.
[src:immunology/immunology] During adolescence, the human body undergoes various physical, physiological and immunological changes triggered and mediated by hormones, of which the most significant in females is 17-β-estradiol (an estrogen) and, in males, is testosterone.
[src:immunology/immunology] Estradiol usually begins to act around the age of 10 and testosterone some months later.
[src:immunology/immunology] There is evidence that these steroids not only act directly on the primary and secondary sexual characteristics but also have an effect on the development and regulation of the immune system, including an increased risk in developing pubescent and post-pubescent autoimmunity.
[src:immunology/immunology] There is also some evidence that cell surface receptors on B cells and macrophages may detect sex hormones in the system.
[src:immunology/immunology] The female sex hormone 17-β-estradiol has been shown to regulate the level of immunological response, while some male androgens such as testosterone seem to suppress the stress response to infection.
[src:immunology/immunology] Other androgens, however, such as DHEA, increase immune response.
[src:immunology/immunology] As in females, the male sex hormones seem to have more control of the immune system during puberty and post-puberty than during the rest of a male's adult life.
[src:immunology/immunology] Physical changes during puberty such as thymic involution also affect immunological response.
[src:immunology/immunology] Ecoimmunology, or ecological immunology, explores the relationship between the immune system of an organism and its social, biotic and abiotic environment.
[src:immunology/immunology] More recent ecoimmunological research has focused on host pathogen defences traditionally considered "non-immunological", such as pathogen avoidance, self-medication, symbiont-mediated defenses, and fecundity trade-offs.
[src:immunology/immunology] Behavioural immunity, a phrase coined by Mark Schaller, specifically refers to psychological pathogen avoidance drivers, such as disgust aroused by stimuli encountered around pathogen-infected individuals, such as the smell of vomit.
[src:immunology/immunology] More broadly, "behavioural" ecological immunity has been demonstrated in multiple species.
[src:immunology/immunology] For example, the Monarch butterfly often lays its eggs on certain toxic milkweed species when infected with parasites.
[src:immunology/immunology] These toxins reduce parasite growth in the offspring of the infected Monarch.
[src:immunology/immunology] However, when uninfected Monarch butterflies are forced to feed only on these toxic plants, they suffer a fitness cost as reduced lifespan relative to other uninfected Monarch butterflies.
[src:immunology/immunology] This indicates that laying eggs on toxic plants is a costly behaviour in Monarchs which has probably evolved to reduce the severity of parasite infection.
[src:immunology/immunology] Symbiont-mediated defenses are also heritable across host generations, despite a non-genetic direct basis for the transmission.
[src:immunology/immunology] Aphids, for example, rely on several different symbionts for defense from key parasites, and can vertically transmit their symbionts from parent to offspring.
[src:immunology/immunology] Therefore, a symbiont that successfully confers protection from a parasite is more likely to be passed to the host offspring, allowing coevolution with parasites attacking the host in a way similar to traditional immunity.
[src:immunology/immunology] The preserved immune tissues of extinct species, such as the thylacine (*Thylacine cynocephalus*), can also provide insights into their biology.
[src:immunology/immunology] The study of the interaction of the immune system with cancer cells can lead to diagnostic tests and therapies with which to find and fight cancer.
[src:immunology/immunology] The immunology concerned with physiological reaction characteristic of the immune state.
[src:immunology/immunology] Inflammation is an immune response that has been observed in many types of cancers.
[src:immunology/immunology] This area of the immunology is devoted to the study of immunological aspects of the reproductive process including fetus acceptance.
[src:immunology/immunology] The term has also been used by fertility clinics to address fertility problems, recurrent miscarriages, premature deliveries and dangerous complications such as pre-eclampsia.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation is a generic response, and therefore is considered a mechanism of innate immunity, not adaptive immunity.
[src:immunology/inflammation] It involves immune cells, blood vessels, and molecular mediators.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The function of inflammation is to eliminate the initial cause of cell injury, clear out damaged cells and tissues, and initiate tissue repair.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation can be classified as *acute* or *chronic*.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammation is the initial response of the body to harmful stimuli, and is achieved by the increased movement of plasma and leukocytes (in particular granulocytes) from the blood into the injured tissues.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A series of biochemical events propagates and matures the inflammatory response, involving the local vascular system, the immune system, and various cells in the injured tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Chronic inflammation is prolonged inflammation that leads to a progressive shift in the type of cells present at the site of inflammation, such as mononuclear cells, and involves simultaneous destruction and healing of the tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation has also been classified as Type 1 and Type 2 based on the type of cytokines and T helper cells (Th1 and Th2) involved.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The first four (classical signs) were described by Celsus (c.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Pain is due to the release of chemicals such as bradykinin and histamine that stimulate nerve endings.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Heat and redness are due to increased blood flow at body core temperature to the inflamed site.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Swelling is caused by accumulation of fluid.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The fifth sign, *loss of function*, is believed to have been added later by Galen, Thomas Sydenham or Rudolf Virchow.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Examples of loss of function include pain that inhibits mobility, severe swelling that prevents movement, having a worse sense of smell during a cold, or having difficulty breathing when bronchitis is present.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammation is a short-term process, usually appearing within a few minutes or hours and begins to cease upon the removal of the injurious stimulus.
[src:immunology/inflammation] It involves a coordinated and systemic mobilization response of various immune, endocrine and neurological mediators of acute inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In a normal healthy response, it becomes activated, clears the pathogen and begins a repair process and then ceases.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammation occurs immediately upon injury, lasting only a few days.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Cytokines and chemokines promote the migration of neutrophils and macrophages to the site of inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Pathogens, allergens, toxins, burns, and frostbite are some of the typical causes of acute inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Toll-like receptors (TLRs) recognize microbial pathogens.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammation can be a defensive mechanism to protect tissues against injury.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation lasting 2–6 weeks is designated subacute inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The process of acute inflammation is initiated by resident immune cells already present in the involved tissue, mainly resident macrophages, dendritic cells, histiocytes, Kupffer cells and mast cells.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These cells possess surface receptors known as pattern recognition receptors (PRRs), which recognize (i.e., bind) two subclasses of molecules: pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) and damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs).
[src:immunology/inflammation] PAMPs are compounds that are associated with various pathogens, but which are distinguishable from host molecules.
[src:immunology/inflammation] DAMPs are compounds that are associated with host-related injury and cell damage.
[src:immunology/inflammation] At the onset of an infection, burn, or other injuries, these cells undergo activation (one of the PRRs recognize a PAMP or DAMP) and release inflammatory mediators responsible for the clinical signs of inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Vasodilation and its resulting increased blood flow causes the redness (*rubor*) and increased heat (*calor*).
[src:immunology/inflammation] Increased permeability of the blood vessels results in an exudation (leakage) of plasma proteins and fluid into the tissue (edema), which manifests itself as swelling (*tumor*).
[src:immunology/inflammation] Some of the released mediators such as bradykinin increase the sensitivity to pain (hyperalgesia, *dolor*).
[src:immunology/inflammation] The mediator molecules also alter the blood vessels to permit the migration of leukocytes, mainly neutrophils and macrophages, to flow out of the blood vessels (extravasation) and into the tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The neutrophils migrate along a chemotactic gradient created by the local cells to reach the site of injury.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The loss of function (*functio laesa*) is probably the result of a neurological reflex in response to pain.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In addition to cell-derived mediators, several acellular biochemical cascade systems—consisting of preformed plasma proteins—act in parallel to initiate and propagate the inflammatory response.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These include the complement system activated by bacteria and the coagulation and fibrinolysis systems activated by necrosis (e.g., burn, trauma).
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammation may be regarded as the first line of defense against injury.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammatory response requires constant stimulation to be sustained.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammatory mediators are short-lived and are quickly degraded in the tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Hence, acute inflammation begins to cease once the stimulus has been removed.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Chronic inflammation is inflammation that lasts for months or years.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Macrophages, lymphocytes, and plasma cells predominate in chronic inflammation, in contrast to the neutrophils that predominate in acute inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Diabetes, cardiovascular disease, allergies, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease are examples of diseases mediated by chronic inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Obesity, smoking, stress and insufficient diet are some of the factors that promote chronic inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] As defined, acute inflammation is an immunovascular response to inflammatory stimuli, which can include infection or trauma.
[src:immunology/inflammation] This means acute inflammation can be broadly divided into a vascular phase that occurs first, followed by a cellular phase involving immune cells (more specifically myeloid granulocytes in the acute setting).
[src:immunology/inflammation] The vascular component of acute inflammation involves the movement of plasma fluid, containing important proteins such as fibrin and immunoglobulins (antibodies), into inflamed tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Upon contact with PAMPs, tissue macrophages and mastocytes release vasoactive amines such as histamine and serotonin, as well as eicosanoids such as prostaglandin E2 and leukotriene B4 to remodel the local vasculature.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Macrophages and endothelial cells release nitric oxide.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These mediators vasodilate and permeabilize the blood vessels, which results in the net distribution of blood plasma from the vessel into the tissue space.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The increased collection of fluid into the tissue causes it to swell (edema).
[src:immunology/inflammation] This exuded tissue fluid contains various antimicrobial mediators from the plasma such as complement, lysozyme, antibodies, which can immediately deal damage to microbes, and opsonise the microbes in preparation for the cellular phase.
[src:immunology/inflammation] If the inflammatory stimulus is a lacerating wound, exuded platelets, coagulants, plasmin and kinins can clot the wounded area using vitamin K-dependent mechanisms and provide haemostasis in the first instance.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These clotting mediators also provide a structural staging framework at the inflammatory tissue site in the form of a fibrin lattice – as would construction scaffolding at a construction site – for the purpose of aiding phagocytic debridement and wound repair later on.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Some of the exuded tissue fluid is also funneled by lymphatics to the regional lymph nodes, flushing bacteria along to start the recognition and attack phase of the adaptive immune system.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Acute inflammation is characterized by marked vascular changes, including vasodilation, increased permeability and increased blood flow, which are induced by the actions of various inflammatory mediators.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Vasodilation occurs first at the arteriole level, progressing to the capillary level, and brings about a net increase in the amount of blood present, causing the redness and heat of inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Increased permeability of the vessels results in the movement of plasma into the tissues, with resultant stasis due to the increase in the concentration of the cells within blood – a condition characterized by enlarged vessels packed with cells.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Stasis allows leukocytes to marginate (move) along the endothelium, a process critical to their recruitment into the tissues.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Normal flowing blood prevents this, as the shearing force along the periphery of the vessels moves cells in the blood into the middle of the vessel.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The cellular component involves leukocytes, which normally reside in blood and must move into the inflamed tissue via extravasation to aid in inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Some act as phagocytes, ingesting bacteria, viruses, and cellular debris.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Others release enzymatic granules that damage pathogenic invaders.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Leukocytes also release inflammatory mediators that develop and maintain the inflammatory response.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In general, acute inflammation is mediated by granulocytes, whereas chronic inflammation is mediated by mononuclear cells such as monocytes and lymphocytes.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Various leukocytes, particularly neutrophils, are critically involved in the initiation and maintenance of inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These cells must be able to move to the site of injury from their usual location in the blood, therefore mechanisms exist to recruit and direct leukocytes to the appropriate place.
[src:immunology/inflammation] **Migration across the endothelium, known as*transmigration,*via the process of diapedesis:** Chemokine gradients stimulate the adhered leukocytes to move between adjacent endothelial cells.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The endothelial cells retract and the leukocytes pass through the basement membrane into the surrounding tissue using adhesion molecules such as ICAM-1.
[src:immunology/inflammation] **Movement of leukocytes within the tissue via chemotaxis:** Leukocytes reaching the tissue interstitium bind to extracellular matrix proteins via expressed integrins and CD44 to prevent them from leaving the site.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A variety of molecules behave as chemoattractants, for example, C3a or C5a (the anaphylatoxins), and cause the leukocytes to move along a chemotactic gradient towards the source of inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Extravasated neutrophils in the cellular phase come into contact with microbes at the inflamed tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Phagocytes express cell-surface endocytic pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) that have affinity and efficacy against non-specific microbe-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs).
[src:immunology/inflammation] Most PAMPs that bind to endocytic PRRs and initiate phagocytosis are cell wall components, including complex carbohydrates such as mannans and β-glucans, lipopolysaccharides (LPS), peptidoglycans, and surface proteins.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Endocytic PRRs on phagocytes reflect these molecular patterns, with C-type lectin receptors binding to mannans and β-glucans, and scavenger receptors binding to LPS.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Upon endocytic PRR binding, actin-myosin cytoskeletal rearrangement adjacent to the plasma membrane occurs in a way that endocytoses the plasma membrane containing the PRR-PAMP complex, and the microbe.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Phosphatidylinositol and Vps34-Vps15-Beclin1 signalling pathways have been implicated to traffic the endocytosed phagosome to intracellular lysosomes, where fusion of the phagosome and the lysosome produces a phagolysosome.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The reactive oxygen species, superoxides and hypochlorite bleach within the phagolysosomes then kill microbes inside the phagocyte.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Phagocytic efficacy can be enhanced by opsonization.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Plasma derived complement C3b and antibodies that exude into the inflamed tissue during the vascular phase bind to and coat the microbial antigens.
[src:immunology/inflammation] As well as endocytic PRRs, phagocytes also express opsonin receptors Fc receptor and complement receptor 1 (CR1), which bind to antibodies and C3b, respectively.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The co-stimulation of endocytic PRR and opsonin receptor increases the efficacy of the phagocytic process, enhancing the lysosomal elimination of the infective agent.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Specific patterns of acute and chronic inflammation are seen during particular situations that arise in the body, such as when inflammation occurs on an epithelial surface, or pyogenic bacteria are involved.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammatory abnormalities are a large group of disorders that underlie a vast variety of human diseases.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The immune system is often involved with inflammatory disorders, as demonstrated in both allergic reactions and some myopathies, with many immune system disorders resulting in abnormal inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Non-immune diseases with causal origins in inflammatory processes include cancer, atherosclerosis, and ischemic heart disease.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Atherosclerosis, formerly considered a lipid storage disorder, is now understood as a chronic inflammatory condition involving the arterial walls.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Research has established a fundamental role for inflammation in mediating all stages of atherosclerosis from initiation through progression and, ultimately, the thrombotic complications from it.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These new findings reveal links between traditional risk factors like cholesterol levels and the underlying mechanisms of atherogenesis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Clinical studies have shown that this emerging biology of inflammation in atherosclerosis applies directly to people.
[src:immunology/inflammation] For instance, elevation in markers of inflammation predicts outcomes of people with acute coronary syndromes, independently of myocardial damage.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In addition, low-grade chronic inflammation, as indicated by levels of the inflammatory marker C-reactive protein, prospectively defines risk of atherosclerotic complications, thus adding to prognostic information provided by traditional risk factors, such as LDL levels.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Moreover, certain treatments that reduce coronary risk also limit inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Notably, lipid-lowering medications such as statins have shown anti-inflammatory effects, which may contribute to their efficacy beyond just lowering LDL levels.
[src:immunology/inflammation] This emerging understanding of inflammation's role in atherosclerosis has had significant clinical implications, influencing both risk stratification and therapeutic strategies.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Recent developments in the treatment of atherosclerosis have focused on addressing inflammation directly.
[src:immunology/inflammation] New anti-inflammatory drugs, such as monoclonal antibodies targeting IL-1β, have been studied in large clinical trials, showing promising results in reducing cardiovascular events.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These drugs offer a potential new avenue for treatment, particularly for patients who do not respond adequately to statins.
[src:immunology/inflammation] However, concerns about long-term safety and cost remain significant barriers to widespread adoption.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammatory processes can be triggered by negative cognition or their consequences, such as stress, violence, or deprivation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Negative cognition may therefore contribute to inflammation, which in turn can lead to depression.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A 2019 meta-analysis found that chronic inflammation is associated with a 30% increased risk of developing major depressive disorder, supporting the link between inflammation and mental health.
[src:immunology/inflammation] An allergic reaction, formally known as type 1 hypersensitivity, is the result of an inappropriate immune response triggering inflammation, vasodilation, and nerve irritation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A common example is hay fever, which is caused by a hypersensitive response by mast cells to allergens.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Pre-sensitised mast cells respond by degranulating, releasing vasoactive chemicals such as histamine.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These chemicals propagate an excessive inflammatory response characterised by blood vessel dilation, production of pro-inflammatory molecules, cytokine release, and recruitment of leukocytes.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Severe inflammatory response may mature into a systemic response known as anaphylaxis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammatory myopathies are caused by the immune system inappropriately attacking components of muscle, leading to signs of muscle inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] They may occur in conjunction with other immune disorders, such as systemic sclerosis, and include dermatomyositis, polymyositis, and inclusion body myositis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Due to the central role of leukocytes in the development and propagation of inflammation, defects in leukocyte functionality often result in a decreased capacity for inflammatory defense with subsequent vulnerability to infection.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Dysfunctional leukocytes may be unable to correctly bind to blood vessels due to surface receptor mutations, digest bacteria (Chédiak–Higashi syndrome), or produce microbicides (chronic granulomatous disease).
[src:immunology/inflammation] In addition, diseases affecting the bone marrow may result in abnormal or few leukocytes.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Certain drugs or exogenous chemical compounds are known to affect inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Vitamin A deficiency, for example, causes an increase in inflammatory responses, and anti-inflammatory drugs work specifically by inhibiting the enzymes that produce inflammatory eicosanoids.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Additionally, certain illicit drugs such as cocaine and ecstasy may exert some of their detrimental effects by activating transcription factors intimately involved with inflammation (e.g.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation orchestrates the microenvironment around tumours, contributing to proliferation, survival and migration.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Cancer cells use selectins, chemokines and their receptors for invasion, migration and metastasis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] On the other hand, many cells of the immune system contribute to cancer immunology, suppressing cancer.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Molecular intersection between receptors of steroid hormones, which have important effects on cellular development, and transcription factors that play key roles in inflammation, such as NF-κB, may mediate some of the most critical effects of inflammatory stimuli on cancer cells.
[src:immunology/inflammation] This capacity of a mediator of inflammation to influence the effects of steroid hormones in cells is very likely to affect carcinogenesis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] On the other hand, due to the modular nature of many steroid hormone receptors, this interaction may offer ways to interfere with cancer progression, through targeting of a specific protein domain in a specific cell type.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Such an approach may limit side effects that are unrelated to the tumor of interest, and may help preserve vital homeostatic functions and developmental processes in the organism.
[src:immunology/inflammation] There is some evidence from 2009 to suggest that cancer-related inflammation (CRI) may lead to accumulation of random genetic alterations in cancer cells.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In 1863, Rudolf Virchow hypothesized that the origin of cancer was at sites of chronic inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] As of 2012, chronic inflammation was estimated to contribute to approximately 15% to 25% of human cancers.
[src:immunology/inflammation] An inflammatory mediator is a messenger that acts on blood vessels and/or cells to promote an inflammatory response.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammatory mediators that contribute to neoplasia include prostaglandins, inflammatory cytokines such as IL-1β, TNF-α, IL-6 and IL-15 and chemokines such as IL-8 and GRO-alpha.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These inflammatory mediators, and others, orchestrate an environment that fosters proliferation and survival.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation also causes DNA damages due to the induction of reactive oxygen species (ROS) by various intracellular inflammatory mediators.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In addition, leukocytes and other phagocytic cells attracted to the site of inflammation induce DNA damages in proliferating cells through their generation of ROS and reactive nitrogen species (RNS).
[src:immunology/inflammation] ROS and RNS are normally produced by these cells to fight infection.
[src:immunology/inflammation] ROS, alone, cause more than 20 types of DNA damage.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Oxidative DNA damages cause both mutations and epigenetic alterations.
[src:immunology/inflammation] RNS can also cause mutagenic DNA damages.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A normal cell may undergo carcinogenesis to become a cancer cell if it is frequently subjected to DNA damage during long periods of chronic inflammation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] DNA damages may cause genetic mutations due to inaccurate repair.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In addition, mistakes in the DNA repair process may cause epigenetic alterations.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Mutations and epigenetic alterations that are replicated and provide a selective advantage during somatic cell proliferation may be carcinogenic.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Genome-wide analyses of human cancer tissues reveal that a single typical cancer cell may possess roughly 100 mutations in coding regions, 10–20 of which are "driver mutations" that contribute to cancer development.
[src:immunology/inflammation] However, chronic inflammation also causes epigenetic changes such as DNA methylations, that are often more common than mutations.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Typically, several hundreds to thousands of genes are methylated in a cancer cell (see DNA methylation in cancer).
[src:immunology/inflammation] Sites of oxidative damage in chromatin can recruit complexes that contain DNA methyltransferases (DNMTs), a histone deacetylase (SIRT1), and a histone methyltransferase (EZH2), and thus induce DNA methylation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] DNA methylation of a CpG island in a promoter region may cause silencing of its downstream gene (see CpG site and regulation of transcription in cancer).
[src:immunology/inflammation] DNA repair genes, in particular, are frequently inactivated by methylation in various cancers (see hypermethylation of DNA repair genes in cancer).
[src:immunology/inflammation] A 2018 report evaluated the relative importance of mutations and epigenetic alterations in progression to two different types of cancer.
[src:immunology/inflammation] This report showed that epigenetic alterations were much more important than mutations in generating gastric cancers (associated with inflammation).
[src:immunology/inflammation] However, mutations and epigenetic alterations were of roughly equal importance in generating esophageal squamous cell cancers (associated with tobacco chemicals and acetaldehyde, a product of alcohol metabolism).
[src:immunology/inflammation] It has long been recognized that infection with HIV is characterized not only by development of profound immunodeficiency but also by sustained inflammation and immune activation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A substantial body of evidence implicates chronic inflammation as a critical driver of immune dysfunction, premature appearance of aging-related diseases, and immune deficiency.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Many now regard HIV infection not only as an evolving virus-induced immunodeficiency, but also as chronic inflammatory disease.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Even after the introduction of effective antiretroviral therapy (ART) and effective suppression of viremia in HIV-infected individuals, chronic inflammation persists.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Animal studies also support the relationship between immune activation and progressive cellular immune deficiency: SIVsm infection of its natural nonhuman primate hosts, the sooty mangabey, causes high-level viral replication but limited evidence of disease.
[src:immunology/inflammation] This lack of pathogenicity is accompanied by a lack of inflammation, immune activation and cellular proliferation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In sharp contrast, experimental SIVsm infection of rhesus macaque produces immune activation and AIDS-like disease with many parallels to human HIV infection.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Delineating how CD4 T cells are depleted and how chronic inflammation and immune activation are induced lies at the heart of understanding HIV pathogenesis—one of the top priorities for HIV research by the Office of AIDS Research, National Institutes of Health.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Recent studies demonstrated that caspase-1-mediated pyroptosis, a highly inflammatory form of programmed cell death, drives CD4 T-cell depletion and inflammation by HIV.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These are the two signature events that propel HIV disease progression to AIDS.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Pyroptosis appears to create a pathogenic vicious cycle in which dying CD4 T cells and other immune cells (including macrophages and neutrophils) release inflammatory signals that recruit more cells into the infected lymphoid tissues to die.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The feed-forward nature of this inflammatory response produces chronic inflammation and tissue injury.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Identifying pyroptosis as the predominant mechanism that causes CD4 T-cell depletion and chronic inflammation, provides novel therapeutic opportunities, namely caspase-1 which controls the pyroptotic pathway.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In this regard, pyroptosis of CD4 T cells and secretion of pro-inflammatory cytokines such as IL-1β and IL-18 can be blocked in HIV-infected human lymphoid tissues by addition of the caspase-1 inhibitor VX-765, which has already proven to be safe and well tolerated in phase II human clinical trials.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These findings could propel development of an entirely new class of "anti-AIDS" therapies that act by targeting the host rather than the virus.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Such agents would almost certainly be used in combination with ART.
[src:immunology/inflammation] There is evidence for a link between inflammation and depression.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammatory processes can be triggered by negative cognitions or their consequences, such as stress, violence, or deprivation.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Thus, negative cognitions can cause inflammation that can, in turn, lead to depression.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In addition, there is increasing evidence that inflammation can cause depression because of the increase of cytokines, setting the brain into a "sickness mode".
[src:immunology/inflammation] Classical symptoms of being physically sick, such as lethargy, show a large overlap in behaviors that characterize depression.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Levels of cytokines tend to increase sharply during the depressive episodes of people with bipolar disorder and drop off during remission.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Furthermore, it has been shown in clinical trials that anti-inflammatory medicines taken in addition to antidepressants not only significantly improves symptoms but also increases the proportion of subjects positively responding to treatment.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammations that lead to serious depression could be caused by common infections such as those caused by a virus, bacteria or even parasites.
[src:immunology/inflammation] There is evidence for a link between inflammation and delirium based on the results of a recent longitudinal study investigating CRP in COVID-19 patients.
[src:immunology/inflammation] An infectious organism can escape the confines of the immediate tissue via the circulatory system or lymphatic system, where it may spread to other parts of the body.
[src:immunology/inflammation] If an organism is not contained by the actions of acute inflammation, it may gain access to the lymphatic system via nearby lymph vessels.
[src:immunology/inflammation] An infection of the lymph vessels is known as lymphangitis, and infection of a lymph node is known as lymphadenitis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] When lymph nodes cannot destroy all pathogens, the infection spreads further.
[src:immunology/inflammation] A pathogen can gain access to the bloodstream through lymphatic drainage into the circulatory system.
[src:immunology/inflammation] When inflammation overwhelms the host, systemic inflammatory response syndrome is diagnosed.
[src:immunology/inflammation] When it is due to infection, the term sepsis is applied, with the terms bacteremia being applied specifically for bacterial sepsis and viremia specifically to viral sepsis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Vasodilation and organ dysfunction are serious problems associated with widespread infection that may lead to septic shock and death.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation also is characterized by high systemic levels of acute-phase proteins.
[src:immunology/inflammation] In acute inflammation, these proteins prove beneficial; however, in chronic inflammation, they can contribute to amyloidosis.
[src:immunology/inflammation] With the discovery of interleukins (IL), the concept of systemic inflammation developed.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Although the processes involved are identical to tissue inflammation, systemic inflammation is not confined to a particular tissue but involves the endothelium and other organ systems.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Chronic inflammation is widely observed in obesity.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Low-grade chronic inflammation is characterized by a two- to threefold increase in the systemic concentrations of cytokines such as TNF-α, IL-6, and CRP.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Waist circumference correlates significantly with systemic inflammatory response.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Loss of white adipose tissue reduces levels of inflammation markers.
[src:immunology/inflammation] As of 2017 the association of systemic inflammation with insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes, and with atherosclerosis was under preliminary research, although rigorous clinical trials had not been conducted to confirm such relationships.
[src:immunology/inflammation] C-reactive protein (CRP) is generated at a higher level in obese people, and may increase the risk for cardiovascular diseases.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The outcome in a particular circumstance will be determined by the tissue in which the injury has occurred—and the injurious agent that is causing it.
[src:immunology/inflammation] **Fibrosis** Large amounts of tissue destruction, or damage in tissues unable to regenerate, cannot be regenerated completely by the body.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Fibrous scarring occurs in these areas of damage, forming a scar composed primarily of collagen.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The scar will not contain any specialized structures, such as parenchymal cells, hence functional impairment may occur.
[src:immunology/inflammation] **Abscess formation** A cavity is formed containing pus, an opaque liquid containing dead white blood cells and bacteria with general debris from destroyed cells.
[src:immunology/inflammation] **Chronic inflammation** In acute inflammation, if the injurious agent persists then chronic inflammation will ensue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] This process, marked by inflammation lasting many days, months or even years, may lead to the formation of a chronic wound.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Chronic inflammation is characterised by the dominating presence of macrophages in the injured tissue.
[src:immunology/inflammation] These cells are powerful defensive agents of the body, but the toxins they release—including reactive oxygen species—are injurious to the organism's own tissues as well as invading agents.
[src:immunology/inflammation] As a consequence, chronic inflammation is almost always accompanied by tissue destruction.
[src:immunology/inflammation] The inflammatory response must be actively terminated when no longer needed to prevent unnecessary "bystander" damage to tissues.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Failure to do so results in chronic inflammation, and cellular destruction.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Resolution of inflammation occurs by different mechanisms in different tissues.
[src:immunology/inflammation] Inflammation is usually indicated by adding the suffix "itis", as shown below.
[src:immunology/inflammation] However, some conditions, such as asthma and pneumonia, do not follow this convention.
[src:immunology/inflammation] More examples are available at List of types of inflammation.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The **innate immune system** or **nonspecific immune system** is one of the two main immunity strategies in vertebrates (the other being the adaptive immune system).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The innate immune system is an alternate defense strategy and is the dominant immune system response found in plants, fungi, prokaryotes, and invertebrates (see § Beyond vertebrates).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Anatomical barriers include physical, chemical and biological barriers.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The epithelial surfaces form a physical barrier that is impermeable to most infectious agents, acting as the first line of defense against invading organisms.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Desquamation (shedding) of skin epithelium also helps remove bacteria and other infectious agents that have adhered to the epithelial surface.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Lack of blood vessels, the inability of the epidermis to retain moisture, and the presence of sebaceous glands in the dermis, produces an environment unsuitable for the survival of microbes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In the gastrointestinal and respiratory tract, movement due to peristalsis or cilia, respectively, helps remove infectious agents.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Gut flora can prevent the colonization of pathogenic bacteria by secreting toxic substances or by competing with pathogenic bacteria for nutrients or cell surface attachment sites.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The flushing action of tears and saliva helps prevent infection of the eyes and mouth.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Barrier impairment occurs in the skin, respiratory tract, and intestines, and is often accompanied by microbial dysbiosis, bacterial translocation, tissue and systemic inflammation, and immune dysregulation.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These processes have been proposed as contributing factors to allergic, autoimmune, metabolic, and neuropsychiatric disorders.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The hypothesis was initially framed in the early 2020s by immunologist Cezmi Akdis and has since been discussed in independent peer-reviewed reviews in the fields of immunology, allergy, dermatology, and nutrition.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Akdis introduced the concept to explain the rising prevalence of chronic inflammatory diseases in industrialized societies.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] It builds on earlier frameworks such as the hygiene hypothesis, and incorporates findings from microbiome research.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Critics of the theory argue that many associations remain correlative and emphasize the need for longitudinal human studies and standardized methods to assess epithelial barrier integrity.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Inflammation is one of the first responses of the immune system to infection or irritation.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Inflammation is stimulated by chemical factors released by injured cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] It establishes a physical barrier against the spread of infection and promotes healing of any damaged tissue following pathogen clearance.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The process of acute inflammation is initiated by cells already present in all tissues, mainly resident macrophages, dendritic cells, histiocytes, Kupffer cells, and mast cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These cells present receptors contained on the surface or within the cell, named *pattern recognition receptors* (PRRs), which recognize molecules that are broadly shared by pathogens but distinguishable from host molecules, collectively referred to as pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] At the onset of an infection, burn, or other injuries, these cells undergo activation (one of their PRRs recognizes a PAMP) and release inflammatory mediators, like cytokines and chemokines, which are responsible for the clinical signs of inflammation.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] PRR activation and its cellular consequences have been well-characterized as methods of inflammatory cell death, which include pyroptosis, necroptosis, and PANoptosis.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These cell death pathways help clear infected or aberrant cells and release cellular contents and inflammatory mediators.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Chemical factors produced during inflammation (histamine, bradykinin, serotonin, leukotrienes, and prostaglandins) sensitize pain receptors, cause local vasodilation of the blood vessels, and attract phagocytes, especially neutrophils.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Neutrophils then trigger other parts of the immune system by releasing factors that summon additional leukocytes and lymphocytes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Cytokines produced by macrophages and other cells of the innate immune system mediate the inflammatory response.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These cytokines include TNF, HMGB1, and IL-1.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The complement system is a key mechanism of innate immunity that utilize proteins to identify and eliminate pathogens, while also maintaining homeostasis by clearing dead and damaged cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Once a pathogen enters the body through the epithelial barrier, soluble plasma proteins called complement proteins become activated (proteins C1-C9).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These complement proteins trigger a cascade of reactions that target and kill extracellular pathogens.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In the classical pathway, The antibody in the classical pathway is produced by B cells during the adaptive immune response, and once it binds to a pathogen, it allows C1 to bind and activate the complement system.This then activates C4 and C2 which will both combine to form C3 convertase.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] C3 convertase will then split into C3a and C3b.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The alternative pathway follows a similar sequence as the classical pathway but begins with the spontaneous activation of C3.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Activated C3 will bind directly to the pathogen’s surface and interacts with other proteins to form C3 convertase.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] At this point, the pathway will continue like the classical pathway and form the membrane attack complex and kill the pathogen via cell lysis.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] C3 is mechanistically essential for complement function, and deficiencies in C3 severely impair immune responses.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] A lack of C3-mediated opsonization is associated with defective dendritic cell differentiation, weakened memory B-cell responses, and impaired regulatory T-cell development, highlighting how C3 influences not only pathogen clearance but also broader adaptive immune processes (Zarantonello, 2022).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Elements of the complement cascade can be found in many non-mammalian species including plants, birds, fish, and some species of invertebrates.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] White blood cells (WBCs) are also known as leukocytes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Most leukocytes differ from other cells of the body in that they are not tightly associated with a particular organ or tissue; thus, their function is similar to that of independent, single-cell organisms.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Most leukocytes are able to move freely and interact with and capture cellular debris, foreign particles, and invading microorganisms (although macrophages, mast cells, and dendritic cells are less mobile).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Unlike many other cells, most innate immune leukocytes cannot divide or reproduce on their own, but are the products of multipotent hematopoietic stem cells present in bone marrow.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The innate leukocytes include: natural killer cells, mast cells, eosinophils, basophils; and the phagocytic cells include macrophages, neutrophils, and dendritic cells, and function within the immune system by identifying and eliminating pathogens that might cause infection.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Mast cells are a type of innate immune cell that resides in connective tissue and in mucous membranes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] They are intimately associated with wound healing and defense against pathogens, but are also often associated with allergy and anaphylaxis.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] When activated, mast cells rapidly release characteristic granules, rich in histamine and heparin, along with various hormonal mediators and chemokines, or chemotactic cytokines into the environment.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Histamine dilates blood vessels, causing the characteristic signs of inflammation, and recruits neutrophils and macrophages.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The word 'phagocyte' literally means 'eating cell'.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These are immune cells that engulf, or 'phagocytose', pathogens or particles.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] To engulf a particle or pathogen, a phagocyte extends portions of its plasma membrane, wrapping the membrane around the particle until it is enveloped (i.e., the particle is now inside the cell).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Once inside the cell, the invading pathogen is contained inside a phagosome, which merges with a lysosome.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The lysosome contains enzymes and acids that kill and digest the particle or organism.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In general, phagocytes patrol the body searching for pathogens, but are also able to react to a group of highly specialized molecular signals produced by other cells, called cytokines.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The phagocytic cells of the immune system include macrophages, neutrophils, and dendritic cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Phagocytosis of the hosts' own cells is common as part of regular tissue development and maintenance.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] When host cells die, either by apoptosis or by cell injury due to an infection, phagocytic cells are responsible for their removal from the affected site.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] By helping to remove dead cells preceding growth and development of new healthy cells, phagocytosis is an important part of the healing process following tissue injury.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Macrophages, from the Greek, meaning "large eaters", are large phagocytic leukocytes, which are able to move beyond the vascular system by migrating through the walls of capillary vessels and entering the areas between cells in pursuit of invading pathogens.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In tissues, organ-specific macrophages are differentiated from phagocytic cells present in the blood called monocytes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Macrophages are the most efficient phagocytes and can phagocytose substantial numbers of bacteria or other cells or microbes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The binding of bacterial molecules to receptors on the surface of a macrophage triggers it to engulf and destroy the bacteria through the generation of a "respiratory burst", causing the release of reactive oxygen species.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Pathogens also stimulate the macrophage to produce chemokines, which summon other cells to the site of infection.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] There are also resident macrophages in many tissues including mucous membranes, liver, lungs, and skin (where they are often called Langerhans cells).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Neutrophils, along with eosinophils and basophils, are known as granulocytes due to the presence of granules in their cytoplasm, or as polymorphonuclear cells (PMNs) due to their distinctive lobed nuclei.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Neutrophil granules contain a variety of toxic substances that kill or inhibit growth of bacteria and fungi.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Similar to macrophages, neutrophils attack pathogens by activating a respiratory burst.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The main products of the neutrophil respiratory burst are strong oxidizing agents including hydrogen peroxide, free oxygen radicals and hypochlorite.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Neutrophils are the most abundant type of phagocyte, normally representing 50–60% of the total circulating leukocytes, and are usually the first cells to arrive at the site of an infection.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The bone marrow of a normal healthy adult produces more than 100 billion neutrophils per day, and more than 10 times that many per day during acute inflammation.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Dendritic cells (DCs) are phagocytic cells present in tissues that are in contact with the external environment, mainly the skin and the inner mucosal lining of the nose, lungs, stomach, and intestines.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] They are named for their resemblance to neuronal dendrites, but dendritic cells are not connected to the nervous system.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Dendritic cells are very important in the process of antigen presentation, and serve as a link between the innate and adaptive immune systems.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Basophils and eosinophils are cells related to the neutrophil.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] When activated by a pathogen encounter, histamine-releasing basophils are important in the defense against parasites and play a role in allergic reactions, such as asthma.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Upon activation, eosinophils secrete a range of highly toxic proteins and free radicals that are highly effective in killing parasites, but may also damage tissue during an allergic reaction.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Activation and release of toxins by eosinophils are, therefore, tightly regulated to prevent any inappropriate tissue destruction.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Natural killer cells (NK cells) do not directly attack invading microbes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] This term describes cells with abnormally low levels of a cell-surface marker called MHC I (major histocompatibility complex) - a situation that can arise in viral infections of host cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] They were named "natural killer" because of the initial notion that they do not require activation in order to kill cells that are "missing self".
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The MHC makeup on the surface of damaged cells is altered and the NK cells become activated by recognizing this.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Those MHC antigens are recognized by killer cell immunoglobulin receptors (KIR) that slow the reaction of NK cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The NK-92 cell line does not express KIR and is developed for tumor therapy.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The various subsets may be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells will respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The coagulation system overlaps with the immune system.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Some products of the coagulation system can contribute to non-specific defenses via their ability to increase vascular permeability and act as chemotactic agents for phagocytic cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In addition, some of the products of the coagulation system are directly antimicrobial.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] For example, beta-lysine, a protein produced by platelets during coagulation, can cause lysis of many Gram-positive bacteria by acting as a cationic detergent.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Many acute-phase proteins of inflammation are involved in the coagulation system.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Increased levels of lactoferrin and transferrin inhibit bacterial growth by binding iron, an essential bacterial nutrient.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The innate immune response to infectious and sterile injury is modulated by neural circuits that control cytokine production period.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The inflammatory reflex is a prototypical neural circuit that controls cytokine production in the spleen.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Action potentials transmitted via the vagus nerve to the spleen mediate the release of acetylcholine, the neurotransmitter that inhibits cytokine release by interacting with alpha7 nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (CHRNA7) expressed on cytokine-producing cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The motor arc of the inflammatory reflex is termed the cholinergic anti-inflammatory pathway.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The parts of the innate immune system display specificity for different pathogens.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Innate immune system cells prevent free growth of microorganisms within the body, but many pathogens have evolved mechanisms to evade it.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] One strategy is intracellular replication, as practised by *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, or wearing a protective capsule, which prevents lysis by complement and by phagocytes, as in *Salmonella*.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] *Bacteroides* species are normally mutualistic bacteria, making up a substantial portion of the mammalian gastrointestinal flora.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Species such as *B. fragilis* are opportunistic pathogens, causing infections of the peritoneal cavity.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] They inhibit phagocytosis by affecting the phagocytes receptors used to engulf bacteria.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] They may also mimic host cells so the immune system does not recognize them as foreign.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] *Staphylococcus aureus* inhibits the ability of the phagocyte to respond to chemokine signals.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] *M. tuberculosis*, *Streptococcus pyogenes*, and *Bacillus anthracis* utilize mechanisms that directly kill the phagocyte.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Bacteria and fungi may form complex biofilms, protecting them from immune cells and proteins; biofilms are present in the chronic *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and *Burkholderia cenocepacia* infections characteristic of cystic fibrosis.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Type I interferons (IFN), secreted mainly by dendritic cells, play a central role in antiviral host defense and a cell's antiviral state.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Viral components are recognized by different receptors: Toll-like receptors are located in the endosomal membrane and recognize double-stranded RNA (dsRNA), MDA5 and RIG-I receptors are located in the cytoplasm and recognize long dsRNA and phosphate-containing dsRNA respectively.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] When the cytoplasmic receptors MDA5 and RIG-I recognize a virus the conformation between the caspase-recruitment domain (CARD) and the CARD-containing adaptor MAVS changes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In parallel, when TLRs in the endocytic compartments recognize a virus the activation of the adaptor protein TRIF is induced.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] IFN is secreted through secretory vesicles, where it can activate receptors on both the cell it was released from (autocrine) or nearby cells (paracrine).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] This induces hundreds of interferon-stimulated genes to be expressed.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] This leads to antiviral protein production, such as protein kinase R, which inhibits viral protein synthesis, or the 2′,5′-oligoadenylate synthetase family, which degrades viral RNA.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Some viruses evade this by producing molecules that interfere with IFN production.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] For example, the Influenza A virus produces NS1 protein, which can bind to host and viral RNA, interact with immune signaling proteins or block their activation by ubiquitination, thus inhibiting type I IFN production.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Influenza A also blocks protein kinase R activation and establishment of the antiviral state.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The dengue virus also inhibits type I IFN production by blocking IRF3 phosphorylation using NS2B3 protease complex.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Cancerous cells exhibit abnormal intercellular signals that normally cause them to be targeted and destroyed by immune cells, such as natural killer cells and cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] To become malignant, a tumor must evade the initial immune response and rewire the immune network in the tumor microenvironment, a process known as immune editing.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Bacteria (and perhaps other prokaryotic organisms), utilize a unique defense mechanism, called the restriction modification system to protect themselves from pathogens, such as bacteriophages.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In this system, bacteria produce enzymes, called restriction endonucleases, that attack and destroy specific regions of the viral DNA of invading bacteriophages.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Methylation of the host's own DNA marks it as "self" and prevents it from being attacked by endonucleases.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Restriction endonucleases and the restriction modification system exist exclusively in prokaryotes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Invertebrates do not possess lymphocytes or an antibody-based humoral immune system, and it is likely that a multicomponent, adaptive immune system arose with the first vertebrates.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Nevertheless, invertebrates possess mechanisms that appear to be precursors of these aspects of vertebrate immunity.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) are proteins used by nearly all organisms to identify molecules associated with microbial pathogens.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] TLRs are a major class of pattern recognition receptor, that exists in all coelomates (animals with a body-cavity), including humans.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The complement system exists in most life forms.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Some invertebrates, including various insects, crabs, and worms utilize a modified form of the complement response known as the prophenoloxidase (proPO) system.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Antimicrobial peptides are an evolutionarily conserved component of the innate immune response found among all classes of life and represent the main form of invertebrate systemic immunity.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Several species of insect produce antimicrobial peptides known as *defensins* and *cecropins*.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In invertebrates, PRRs trigger proteolytic cascades that degrade proteins and control many of the mechanisms of the innate immune system of invertebrates—including hemolymph coagulation and melanization.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Proteolytic cascades are important components of the invertebrate immune system because they are turned on more rapidly than other innate immune reactions because they do not rely on gene changes.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Proteolytic cascades function in both vertebrate and invertebrates, even though different proteins are used throughout the cascades.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In the hemolymph, which makes up the fluid in the circulatory system of arthropods, a gel-like fluid surrounds pathogen invaders, similar to the way blood does in other animals.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Various proteins and mechanisms are involved in invertebrate clotting.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In crustaceans, transglutaminase from blood cells and mobile plasma proteins make up the clotting system, where the transglutaminase polymerizes 210 kDa subunits of a plasma-clotting protein.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] On the other hand, in the horseshoe crab clotting system, components of proteolytic cascades are stored as inactive forms in granules of hemocytes, which are released when foreign molecules, like lipopolysaccharides enter.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Members of every class of pathogen that infect humans also infect plants.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Although the exact pathogenic species vary with the infected species, bacteria, fungi, viruses, nematodes, and insects can all cause plant disease.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] As with animals, plants attacked by insects or other pathogens use a set of complex metabolic responses that lead to the formation of defensive chemical compounds that fight infection or make the plant less attractive to insects and other herbivores.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Like invertebrates, plants neither generate antibody or T-cell responses nor possess mobile cells that detect and attack pathogens.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] In addition, in case of infection, parts of some plants are treated as disposable and replaceable, in ways that few animals can.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Walling off or discarding a part of a plant helps stop infection spread.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Most plant immune responses involve systemic chemical signals sent throughout a plant.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Plants use PRRs to recognize conserved microbial signatures.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] This recognition triggers an immune response.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The first plant receptors of conserved microbial signatures were identified in rice (XA21, 1995) and in *Arabidopsis* (FLS2, 2000).
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Plants also carry immune receptors that recognize variable pathogen effectors.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These include the NBS-LRR class of proteins.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] HR has some similarities to animal pyroptosis, such as a requirement of caspase-1-like proteolytic activity of VPEγ, a cysteine protease that regulates cell disassembly during cell death.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] "Resistance" (R) proteins, encoded by R genes, are widely present in plants and detect pathogens.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] These proteins contain domains similar to the NOD Like Receptors and TLRs.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Systemic acquired resistance (SAR) is a type of defensive response that renders the entire plant resistant to a broad spectrum of infectious agents.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] SAR involves the production of chemical messengers, such as salicylic acid or jasmonic acid.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Some of these travel through the plant and signal other cells to produce defensive compounds to protect uninfected parts, e.g., leaves.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Salicylic acid itself, although indispensable for expression of SAR, is not the translocated signal responsible for the systemic response.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] Recent evidence indicates a role for jasmonates in transmission of the signal to distal portions of the plant.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] RNA silencing mechanisms are important in the plant systemic response, as they can block virus replication.
[src:immunology/innate-immune-system] The *jasmonic acid response* is stimulated in leaves damaged by insects, and involves the production of methyl jasmonate.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] In a multicellular organism's immune system, phagocytosis is a major mechanism used to remove pathogens and cell debris.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The ingested material is then digested in the phagosome.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Bacteria, dead tissue cells, and small mineral particles are all examples of objects that may be phagocytized.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Some protozoa use phagocytosis as means to obtain nutrients.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The two main cells that do this are the Macrophages and the Neutrophils of the immune system.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Where phagocytosis is used as a means of feeding and provides the organism part or all of its nourishment, it is called **phagotrophy** and is distinguished from osmotrophy, which is nutrition taking place by absorption.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The history of phagocytosis represents the scientific establishment of immunology as the process is the first immune response mechanism discovered and understood as such.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The earliest definitive account of cell eating was given by Swiss scientist Albert von Kölliker in 1849.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The first demonstration of phagocytosis as a property of leucocytes, the immune cells, was from the German zoologist Ernst Haeckel.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Haeckel discovered that blood cells of sea slug, *Tethys*, could ingest Indian ink (or indigo) particles.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] It was the first direct evidence of phagocytosis by immune cells.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Phagocytosis was noted by Canadian physician William Osler (1876), and later studied and named by Élie Metchnikoff (1880, 1883).
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Phagocytosis is one main mechanisms of the innate immune defense.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] It is one of the first processes responding to infection, and is also one of the initiating branches of an adaptive immune response.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Although most cells are capable of phagocytosis, some cell types perform it as part of their main function.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] These are called 'professional phagocytes.' Phagocytosis is old in evolutionary terms, being present even in invertebrates.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Neutrophils, macrophages, monocytes, dendritic cells, osteoclasts and eosinophils can be classified as professional phagocytes.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The first three have the greatest role in immune response to most infections.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The role of neutrophils is patrolling the bloodstream and rapid migration to the tissues in large numbers only in case of infection.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] There they have direct microbicidal effect by phagocytosis.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] After ingestion, neutrophils are efficient in intracellular killing of pathogens.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Neutrophils phagocytose mainly via the Fcγ receptors and complement receptors 1 and 3.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The microbicidal effect of neutrophils is due to a large repertoire of molecules present in pre-formed granules.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Enzymes and other molecules prepared in these granules are proteases, such as collagenase, gelatinase or serine proteases, myeloperoxidase, lactoferrin and antibiotic proteins.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Degranulation of these into the phagosome, accompanied by high reactive oxygen species production (oxidative burst) is highly microbicidal.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Monocytes, and the macrophages that mature from them, leave blood circulation to migrate through tissues.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] There they are resident cells and form a resting barrier.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Macrophages initiate phagocytosis by mannose receptors, scavenger receptors, Fcγ receptors and complement receptors 1, 3 and 4.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Macrophages are long-lived and can continue phagocytosis by forming new lysosomes.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Dendritic cells also reside in tissues and ingest pathogens by phagocytosis.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Their role is not killing or clearance of microbes, but rather breaking them down for antigen presentation to the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Receptors for phagocytosis can be divided into two categories by recognised molecules.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The first, opsonic receptors, are dependent on opsonins.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Among these are receptors that recognise the Fc part of bound IgG antibodies, deposited complement or receptors, that recognise other opsonins of cell or plasma origin.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Non-opsonic receptors include lectin-type receptors, Dectin receptor, or scavenger receptors.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Some phagocytic pathways require a second signal from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) activated by attachment to pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPS), which leads to NF-κB activation.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Fcγ receptors recognise IgG coated targets.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The main recognised part is the Fc fragment.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The molecule of the receptor contain an intracellular ITAM domain or associates with an ITAM-containing adaptor molecule.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] ITAM domains transduce the signal from the surface of the phagocyte to the nucleus.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] For example, activating receptors of human macrophages are FcγRI, FcγRIIA, and FcγRIII.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Fcγ receptor mediated phagocytosis includes formation of protrusions of the cell called a 'phagocytic cup' and activates an oxidative burst in neutrophils.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] These receptors recognise targets coated in C3b, C4b and C3bi from plasma complement.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The extracellular domain of the receptors contains a lectin-like complement-binding domain.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Recognition by complement receptors is not enough to cause internalisation without additional signals.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] In macrophages, the CR1, CR3 and CR4 are responsible for recognition of targets.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Complement coated targets are internalised by 'sinking' into the phagocyte membrane, without any protrusions.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Mannose and other pathogen-associated sugars, such as fucose, are recognised by the mannose receptor.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Eight lectin-like domains form the extracellular part of the receptor.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The ingestion mediated by the mannose receptor is distinct in molecular mechanisms from Fcγ receptor or complement receptor mediated phagocytosis.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Engulfment of material is facilitated by the actin-myosin contractile system.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The phagosome is the organelle formed by phagocytosis of material.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] It then moves toward the centrosome of the phagocyte and is fused with lysosomes, forming a phagolysosome and leading to degradation.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Progressively, the phagolysosome is acidified, activating degradative enzymes.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Degradation can be oxygen-dependent or oxygen-independent.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Leukocytes generate hydrogen cyanide during phagocytosis, and can kill bacteria, fungi, and other pathogens by generating several other toxic chemicals.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Some bacteria, for example *Treponema pallidum*, *Escherichia coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*, are able to avoid phagocytosis by several mechanisms.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Following apoptosis, the dying cells need to be taken up into the surrounding tissues by macrophages in a process called efferocytosis.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] One of the features of an apoptotic cell is the presentation of a variety of intracellular molecules on the cell surface, such as calreticulin, phosphatidylserine (from the inner layer of the plasma membrane), annexin A1, oxidised LDL and altered glycans.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Defects in apoptotic cell clearance is usually associated with impaired phagocytosis of macrophages.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Accumulation of apoptotic cell remnants often causes autoimmune disorders; thus pharmacological potentiation of phagocytosis has a medical potential in treatment of certain forms of autoimmune disorders.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Phagocytosis is used by many protists as a means of feeding, thus constituting phagotrophy.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] As in phagocytic immune cells, the resulting phagosome may be merged with lysosomes (food vacuoles) containing digestive enzymes, forming a phagolysosome.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] The food particles will then be digested, and the released nutrients are diffused or transported into the cytosol for use in other metabolic processes.
[src:immunology/phagocytosis] Mixotrophy can involve phagotrophic nutrition and phototrophic nutrition.
